{"title_page": "Who's Gonna Save Us?", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Who's Gonna Save Us?\n| cover      = Wgsu.gif\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Living End]]\n| album      = [[Modern ARTillery]]\n| released   = September 29, 2003\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 03:21\n| label      = [[EMI]]\n| writer     = [[Chris Cheney]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[One Said To The Other]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n\"'''Who's Gonna Save Us?'''\" is a song by Australian [[punk rock]] band [[The Living End]]. It was released in September 2003, as the first [[Single (music)|single]] (not including ''One Said to the Other'' as it was re-recorded for the album) from the band's third album, ''[[Modern Artillery|Modern ARTillery]]''. \n\nIt reached number 37 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] and also charted in the United States, peaking at number 26 on the [[Alternative Songs|Hot Modern Rock Tracks]]. The song appeared in the television commercial and soundtrack for [[Michael Moore]]'s 2004 documentary film, ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = \n| title1          = Who's Gonna Save Us?\n| length1         = 3:21\n\n| title2          = No Return\n| note2   = Demo\n| length2         =\n\n| title3          = The Avenue\n| length3         =\n| note3 = Demo\n\n| title4          = Just Too Bad\n| length4         = \n| note4 = Demo\n}}\n\n<small>Recorded and engineered by Lindsay Gravina at [[Sing Sing Studios]], [[Melbourne]]. Mixed by [[Jerry Finn]] at The Mastering Lab, [[Los Angeles]].</small>\n\n{{The Living End}}\n\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:The Living End songs]]\n[[Category:EMI Records singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Chris Cheney]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Who's Gonna Save Us?\n| cover      = Wgsu.gif\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Living End]]\n| album      = [[Modern ARTillery]]\n| released   = September 29, 2003\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 03:21\n| label      = [[EMI]]\n| writer     = [[Chris Cheney]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[One Said To The Other]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n\"'''Who's Gonna Save Us?'''\" is a song by Australian [[punk rock]] band [[The Living End]]. It was released in September 2003, as the first [[Single (music)|single]] (not including ''One Said to the Other'' as it was re-recorded for the album) from the band's third album, ''[[Modern Artillery|Modern ARTillery]]''. \n\nIt reached number 37 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] and also charted in the United States, peaking at number 26 on the [[Alternative Songs|Hot Modern Rock Tracks]]. The song appeared in the television commercial and soundtrack for [[Michael Moore]]'s 2004 documentary film, ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Who's Gonna Save Us?\"\n#\"No Return\" (demo)\n#\"The Avenue\" (demo)\n#\"Just Too Bad\" (demo)\n\n{{The Living End}}\n\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:The Living End songs]]\n[[Category:EMI Records singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Chris Cheney]]\n", "name_user": "Machr123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Who%27s_Gonna_Save_Us%3F"}
{"title_page": "Glooscap First Nation", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Glooscap First Nation\n|motto                  = A community that is spirited and full of life \n|image_skyline          = [[File:Glooscapoffice.jpg|250px|Glooscap First Nation Community Centre & Offices]]\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             = \n|pushpin_map            = Nova Scotia\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 200\n|pushpin_label_position = left\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location of Glooscap First Nation in [[Nova Scotia]]\n|map_caption            = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Canada\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Nova Scotia]]\n|subdivision_type2      = County\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Kings County, Nova Scotia|Kings County]]\n|leader_title           = Chief\n|leader_title1          = Council\n|leader_title2          = Member of Parliament\n|leader_title3          = Member of the Legislative Assembly \n|leader_name            = Sidney Peters\n|leader_name1          = Leonard Peters<br />Jean Labrador-Powers<br />Lynwood Peters\n|leader_name2          = [[Kody Blois]] (L)\n|leader_name3          = [[Keith Irving]] (L)\n|established_title      = Established\n|established_date       = 1907\n|area_magnitude         = \n|area_total_km2             = 1.82\n|area_total_sq_mi        = \n|area_land_km2              = \n|area_land_sq_mi         = \n|area_water_km2             = \n|area_water_sq_mi        = \n|area_water_percent     = \n|area_urban_km2             = \n|area_urban_sq_mi        = \n|area_metro_km2             = \n|area_metro_sq_mi        = \n|population_as_of       = 2019\n|population_note        = \n|population_total       = 393\n|population_blank1_title        = Change&nbsp;<small>2011-16</small>\n|population_blank1              = {{profit}}37.3%\n|population_metro       = \n|population_urban       = \n|population_density_km2     = \n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|timezone               = [[Atlantic Standard Time Zone|Atlantic (AST)]]\n|utc_offset             = -4\n|timezone_DST           = ADT\n|utc_offset_DST         = -3\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|02|25|N|64|13|45|W|region:CA-NS|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|elevation_min_m = 40  \n|elevation_max_m = 100  \n|blank_name            = [[National Topographic System|NTS]] Map\n|blank_info            = 021H01\n|blank1_name            = \n|blank1_info            = \n|website                = http://www.glooscapfirstnation.com/\n|footnotes              = [[Canadian postal code|Postal code]] span: B0P1P0 \n}} <!-- Infobox ends -->\n\n'''Glooscap First Nation''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[Mi'kmaq]] aboriginal community located in both [[Kings County, Nova Scotia|Kings County]] and [[Hants County]], [[Nova Scotia]]. Also known as '''Kluskap''', its reserve is located approximately {{convert|6.4|km}} from the Town of [[Hantsport, Nova Scotia|Hantsport]]. Created in 1907 as '''Horton 35''', the reserve encompasses some {{convert|171.1|ha}} of rolling, mainly forested land. Forest management is practiced by the band.<ref>Mi'kmaq Resource Centre (UCCB), [http://mikmawey.uccb.ns.ca/nscouncils.html#7 Mi'kmaw Bands in Nova Scotia]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> There is a variety store, gas bar, [[Greco Pizza]], and gaming centre. There is also a health centre, youth centre and chapel. The Glooscap Landing Business Park is also owned by Glooscap First Nation which houses a second gas bar and [[Tim Hortons]].<ref>Aboriginal Canada Portal, [http://www.aboriginalcanada.gc.ca/abdt/apps/connectivitysurvey.nsf/vAllCProfile_en/216.html Connectivity Survey] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425062201/http://www.aboriginalcanada.gc.ca/abdt/apps/connectivitysurvey.nsf/vAllCProfile_en/216.html# |date=2010-04-25 }}</ref> The 2019 population was 391 people of whom approximately 100 lived on the reserve, making Glooscap the third-smallest First Nation community in Nova Scotia after [[Bear River First Nation]] and [[Annapolis Valley First Nation]].<ref>http://fnp-ppn.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/fnp/Main/Search/FNRegPopulation.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=30&lang=eng</ref>\n\t\n;Reserves\n* [[Glooscap 35, Nova Scotia|Glooscap 35]]\n\n==History==\n\nGlooscap was created in 1907 from land owned by [[Silas Tertius Rand]], a missionary of the Micmac Missionary Society. Rand purchased 450 acres close to the town of [[Hantsport]] so they could make a living selling artwork in the marketplace. The reserve was called Horton but administered by [[Annapolis Valley First Nation]] 30&nbsp;km away in Cambridge.<ref>http://mikmaqrights.com/our-community/communities/glooscap/</ref> \n\nIn 1984 only one home and family were living in Horton, and they were not receiving adequate service delivery from Annapolis Valley First Nation.<ref>http://mikmaqrights.com/our-community/communities/glooscap/</ref> The Chief of Annapolis Valley First Nation, Chief Rita Smith lead the government advocacy for independence of Horton from Annapolis Valley. In 1984 Horton separated from Annapolis Valley First Nation and became its own independent First Nation reservation. Rita Smith became Horton's first Chief.<ref>http://www.danielnpaul.com/ChiefRitaSmith.html</ref> The community was co-founded by five families: Smith, Peters, Francis, Labrador, and Pictou. \n\n* Rita Smith was elected Chief from 1984 to 1989\n* Joseph Peters was elected Chief from 1989 to 1995\n* Shirley Clarke was elected Chief from 1995 to 2012\n* Sidney Peters was elected Chief from 2012 to present\n\nIn 2001 Horton changed its name to Glooscap First Nation in honour of the legendary hero of the Mi'kmaq. [[Glooscap]]'s home was located nearby at [[Blomidon Provincial Park]], [[Nova Scotia]].<ref>http://mikmaqrights.com/our-community/communities/glooscap/</ref>\n\n==Financial controversies==\nIn 2010 controversy erupted in the news media and on the reserve when it was revealed that band councillors of the tiny community each earn between $210,000 and $260,000 a year and one councillor earned almost a million dollars one fiscal year, after selling a lucrative business on the reserve. Shirley Clarke, Chief of the reserve, defended the council's high salaries saying they work hard and their responsibilities are vast.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/atlantic/leader-of-tiny-native-band-says-she-works-hard-for-243000-pay/article1822953/ Oliver Moore, \"Leader of Tiny Reserve Says She Works Hard for $243,000 pay\", ''Globe and Mail'' Dec. 2, 2010]</ref> Some native organizations have defended the salaries saying they include legitimate expenses.<ref>Media Indigena,[http://www.mediaindigena.com/rickharp/issues-and-politics/atlantic-chief-slams-inaccurate-negative-publicity-over-first-nation-political-salaries-does-she-have-a-point \"First Nations reject inaccurate, negative publicity over salaries\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426071303/http://www.mediaindigena.com/rickharp/issues-and-politics/atlantic-chief-slams-inaccurate-negative-publicity-over-first-nation-political-salaries-does-she-have-a-point |date=2012-04-26 }}, News release, November 23, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2015 staff member Robin Connel was charged with theft of more than $160,000 from a community-owned business. The staff member was the manager of the gas station and gaming centre and was taking funds from the business's safe and depositing the funds into her personal account. The ex-manager was sentenced to two years in prison and to pay back $120,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/glooscap-ex-manager-sentenced-to-2-years-for-stealing-from-store-1.2899273|title=Prison sentence for woman who stole $160K from First Nations store|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-01-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe community is represented by a chief and a three-person council. The community is managed by the director of administration.<ref>Glooscap First Nation, [http://www.glooscapfirstnation.com/chief-council/ Chief&Council] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222002618/http://www.glooscapfirstnation.com/chief-council/ |date=2013-12-22 }}</ref>\nSince 2004, the band and the Town of Hantsport have had a shared water supply.<ref>Province of Nova Scotia, [http://www.gov.ns.ca/news/details.asp?id=20040916001 \"Glooscap and Hantsport Co-operate on Water Project\"], News release, September 16, 2004</ref>\n\nGlooscap has a custom election code which allows the elected chief and councillors to serve five-year terms.<ref>http://www.pampalmater.com/band-elections/</ref>\n\nIn 2012 the Glooscap First Nation held an election. A new Chief and Council was elected, lead again by the Peters family. Sidney Peters, the brother of former Glooscap FN Chief Shirley Clarke, was elected Chief with 55% of the vote in an election that nearly 80% of the membership voted. He is a fifth-generation chief within the Peters family.<ref>CBC, [http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/story/2012/02/26/ns-glooscap-new-chief.html \"Glooscap First Nation elects new chief\"], New release, February 26, 2012</ref>\n\nThe new council implement some new policies and removed some corrupt officials from their offices. They also created a new [[economic development corporation]] to provide more transparency and improve the sustainability of the community.<ref>The Hants Journal, [http://www.hantsjournal.ca/News/Local/2013-12-05/article-3531156/Glooscap-First-Nation-establishing-economic-development-corporation/1 \"Glooscap First Nation establishing economic development corporation\"], News release, December 5, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Sidney Peters was re-elected with 95% of the votes (174 to 12 votes). Two other brothers were elected to council.<ref>''Hants Journal'', \"Glooscap First Nation Re-elects Chief\" [https://www.hantsjournal.ca/news/local/glooscap-first-nation-re-elects-chief-1639/], News release, February 27, 2017, Retrieved 24 July 2019</ref>\n\n==Economic development==\n\nIn 2011, the band formed a new, independently run corporation that has the responsibility of improving the economy and sustainability of Glooscap First Nation. The focus will on building partnerships with neighboring municipalities, businesses and organizations in order to benefit the entire region. The Board of Directors include some high profile and up-and-coming businesspeople.<ref>The Hants Journal, [http://www.hantsjournal.ca/News/Local/2013-12-05/article-3531156/Glooscap-First-Nation-establishing-economic-development-corporation/1 \"Glooscap First Nation establishing economic development corporation\"], News release, December 5, 2013</ref> \n\nThe corporation rebranded to become Glooscap Ventures in 2015 and are currently overseeing the $10 Million, Glooscap Landing Project.<ref>http://www.glooscapventures.com/about-us-1/{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Glooscap was recognized for its economic development on a national scale. They were awarded the 2017 CANDO Indigenous Community Economic Developer of the Year. This award is presented to Canada's top economic development indigenous community on an annual basis.<ref>http://www.kingscountynews.ca/business/glooscap-first-nation-recognized-for-its-economic-growth-at-national-level-159613/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.torontosun.com/2011/11/25/native-spending-must-be-transparent]\n\n{{First Nations in Nova Scotia}}\n\n[[Category:First Nations governments in Atlantic Canada]]\n[[Category:First Nations in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Communities in Kings County, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mi'kmaq governments]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Glooscap First Nation\n|motto                  = A community that is spirited and full of life \n|image_skyline          = [[File:Glooscapoffice.jpg|250px|Glooscap First Nation Community Centre & Offices]]\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             = \n|pushpin_map            = Nova Scotia\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 200\n|pushpin_label_position = left\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location of Glooscap First Nation in [[Nova Scotia]]\n|map_caption            = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Canada\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Nova Scotia]]\n|subdivision_type2      = County\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Kings County, Nova Scotia|Kings County]]\n|leader_title           = Chief\n|leader_title1          = Council\n|leader_title2          = Member of Parliament\n|leader_title3          = Member of the Legislative Assembly \n|leader_name            = Sidney Peters\n|leader_name1          = Leonard Peters<br />Jean Labrador-Powers<br />Lynwood Peters\n|leader_name2          = [[Kody Blois]] (L)\n|leader_name3          = [[Keith Irving]] (L)\n|established_title      = Established\n|established_date       = 1907\n|area_magnitude         = \n|area_total_km2             = 1.82\n|area_total_sq_mi        = \n|area_land_km2              = \n|area_land_sq_mi         = \n|area_water_km2             = \n|area_water_sq_mi        = \n|area_water_percent     = \n|area_urban_km2             = \n|area_urban_sq_mi        = \n|area_metro_km2             = \n|area_metro_sq_mi        = \n|population_as_of       = 2019\n|population_note        = \n|population_total       = 393\n|population_blank1_title        = Change&nbsp;<small>2011-16</small>\n|population_blank1              = {{profit}}37.3%\n|population_metro       = \n|population_urban       = \n|population_density_km2     = \n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|timezone               = [[Atlantic Standard Time Zone|Atlantic (AST)]]\n|utc_offset             = -4\n|timezone_DST           = ADT\n|utc_offset_DST         = -3\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|02|25|N|64|13|45|W|region:CA-NS|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|elevation_min_m = 40  \n|elevation_max_m = 100  \n|blank_name            = [[National Topographic System|NTS]] Map\n|blank_info            = 021H01\n|blank1_name            = \n|blank1_info            = \n|website                = http://www.glooscapfirstnation.com/\n|footnotes              = [[Canadian postal code|Postal code]] span: B0P1P0 \n}} <!-- Infobox ends -->\n\n'''Glooscap First Nation''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[Mi'kmaq]] aboriginal community located in both [[Kings County, Nova Scotia|Kings County]] and [[Hants County]], [[Nova Scotia]]. Also known as '''Kluskap''', its reserve is located approximately {{convert|6.4|km}} from the Town of [[Hantsport, Nova Scotia|Hantsport]]. Created in 1907 as '''Horton 35''', the reserve encompasses some {{convert|171.1|ha}} of rolling, mainly forested land. Forest management is practiced by the band.<ref>Mi'kmaq Resource Centre (UCCB), [http://mikmawey.uccb.ns.ca/nscouncils.html#7 Mi'kmaw Bands in Nova Scotia]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> There is a variety store, gas bar, [[Greco Pizza]], and gaming centre. There is also a health centre, youth centre and chapel. The Glooscap Landing Business Park is also owned by Glooscap First Nation which houses a second gas bar and [[Tim Hortons]].<ref>Aboriginal Canada Portal, [http://www.aboriginalcanada.gc.ca/abdt/apps/connectivitysurvey.nsf/vAllCProfile_en/216.html Connectivity Survey] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425062201/http://www.aboriginalcanada.gc.ca/abdt/apps/connectivitysurvey.nsf/vAllCProfile_en/216.html# |date=2010-04-25 }}</ref> The 2019 population was 391 people of whom approximately 100 lived on the reserve, making Glooscap the third-smallest First Nation community in Nova Scotia after [[Bear River First Nation]] and [[Annapolis Valley First Nation]].<ref>http://fnp-ppn.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/fnp/Main/Search/FNRegPopulation.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=30&lang=eng</ref>\n\t\n;Reserves\n* [[Glooscap 35, Nova Scotia|Glooscap 35]]\n\n==History==\n\nGlooscap was created in 1907 from land owned by [[Silas Tertius Rand]], a missionary of the Micmac Missionary Society. Rand purchased 450 acres close to the town of [[Hantsport]] so they could make a living selling artwork in the marketplace. The reserve was called Horton but administered by [[Annapolis Valley First Nation]] 30&nbsp;km away in Cambridge.<ref>http://mikmaqrights.com/our-community/communities/glooscap/</ref> \n\nIn 1984 only one home and family were living in Horton, and they were not receiving adequate service delivery from Annapolis Valley First Nation.<ref>http://mikmaqrights.com/our-community/communities/glooscap/</ref> The Chief of Annapolis Valley First Nation, Chief Rita Smith lead the government advocacy for independence of Horton from Annapolis Valley. In 1984 Horton separated from Annapolis Valley First Nation and became its own independent First Nation reservation. Rita Smith became Horton's first Chief.<ref>http://www.danielnpaul.com/ChiefRitaSmith.html</ref> The community was co-founded by five families: Smith, Peters, Francis, Labrador, and Pictou. \n\n* Rita Smith was elected Chief from 1984 to 1989\n* Joseph Peters was elected Chief from 1989 to 1995\n* Shirley Clarke was elected Chief from 1995 to 2012\n* Sidney Peters was elected Chief from 2012 to present\n\nIn 2001 Horton changed its name to Glooscap First Nation in honour of the legendary hero of the Mi'kmaq. [[Glooscap]]'s home was located nearby at [[Blomidon Provincial Park]], [[Nova Scotia]].<ref>http://mikmaqrights.com/our-community/communities/glooscap/</ref>\n\n==Financial controversies==\nIn 2010 controversy erupted in the news media and on the reserve when it was revealed that band councillors of the tiny community each earn between $210,000 and $260,000 a year and one councillor earned almost a million dollars one fiscal year, after selling a lucrative business on the reserve. Shirley Clarke, Chief of the reserve, defended the council's high salaries saying they work hard and their responsibilities are vast.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/atlantic/leader-of-tiny-native-band-says-she-works-hard-for-243000-pay/article1822953/ Oliver Moore, \"Leader of Tiny Reserve Says She Works Hard for $243,000 pay\", ''Globe and Mail'' Dec. 2, 2010]</ref> Some native organizations have defended the salaries saying they include legitimate expenses.<ref>Media Indigena,[http://www.mediaindigena.com/rickharp/issues-and-politics/atlantic-chief-slams-inaccurate-negative-publicity-over-first-nation-political-salaries-does-she-have-a-point \"First Nations reject inaccurate, negative publicity over salaries\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426071303/http://www.mediaindigena.com/rickharp/issues-and-politics/atlantic-chief-slams-inaccurate-negative-publicity-over-first-nation-political-salaries-does-she-have-a-point |date=2012-04-26 }}, News release, November 23, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2015 a staff member was charged with theft of more than $160,000 from a community-owned business. The staff member was the manager of the gas station and gaming centre and was taking funds from the business's safe and depositing the funds into her personal account. The ex-manager was sentenced to two years in prison and to pay back $120,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/glooscap-ex-manager-sentenced-to-2-years-for-stealing-from-store-1.2899273|title=Prison sentence for woman who stole $160K from First Nations store|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-01-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe community is represented by a chief and a three-person council. The community is managed by the director of administration.<ref>Glooscap First Nation, [http://www.glooscapfirstnation.com/chief-council/ Chief&Council] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222002618/http://www.glooscapfirstnation.com/chief-council/ |date=2013-12-22 }}</ref>\nSince 2004, the band and the Town of Hantsport have had a shared water supply.<ref>Province of Nova Scotia, [http://www.gov.ns.ca/news/details.asp?id=20040916001 \"Glooscap and Hantsport Co-operate on Water Project\"], News release, September 16, 2004</ref>\n\nGlooscap has a custom election code which allows the elected chief and councillors to serve five-year terms.<ref>http://www.pampalmater.com/band-elections/</ref>\n\nIn 2012 the Glooscap First Nation held an election. A new Chief and Council was elected, lead again by the Peters family. Sidney Peters, the brother of former Glooscap FN Chief Shirley Clarke, was elected Chief with 55% of the vote in an election that nearly 80% of the membership voted. He is a fifth-generation chief within the Peters family.<ref>CBC, [http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/story/2012/02/26/ns-glooscap-new-chief.html \"Glooscap First Nation elects new chief\"], New release, February 26, 2012</ref>\n\nThe new council implement some new policies and removed some corrupt officials from their offices. They also created a new [[economic development corporation]] to provide more transparency and improve the sustainability of the community.<ref>The Hants Journal, [http://www.hantsjournal.ca/News/Local/2013-12-05/article-3531156/Glooscap-First-Nation-establishing-economic-development-corporation/1 \"Glooscap First Nation establishing economic development corporation\"], News release, December 5, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Sidney Peters was re-elected with 95% of the votes (174 to 12 votes). Two other brothers were elected to council.<ref>''Hants Journal'', \"Glooscap First Nation Re-elects Chief\" [https://www.hantsjournal.ca/news/local/glooscap-first-nation-re-elects-chief-1639/], News release, February 27, 2017, Retrieved 24 July 2019</ref>\n\n==Economic development==\n\nIn 2011, the band formed a new, independently run corporation that has the responsibility of improving the economy and sustainability of Glooscap First Nation. The focus will on building partnerships with neighboring municipalities, businesses and organizations in order to benefit the entire region. The Board of Directors include some high profile and up-and-coming businesspeople.<ref>The Hants Journal, [http://www.hantsjournal.ca/News/Local/2013-12-05/article-3531156/Glooscap-First-Nation-establishing-economic-development-corporation/1 \"Glooscap First Nation establishing economic development corporation\"], News release, December 5, 2013</ref> \n\nThe corporation rebranded to become Glooscap Ventures in 2015 and are currently overseeing the $10 Million, Glooscap Landing Project.<ref>http://www.glooscapventures.com/about-us-1/{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Glooscap was recognized for its economic development on a national scale. They were awarded the 2017 CANDO Indigenous Community Economic Developer of the Year. This award is presented to Canada's top economic development indigenous community on an annual basis.<ref>http://www.kingscountynews.ca/business/glooscap-first-nation-recognized-for-its-economic-growth-at-national-level-159613/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.torontosun.com/2011/11/25/native-spending-must-be-transparent]\n\n{{First Nations in Nova Scotia}}\n\n[[Category:First Nations governments in Atlantic Canada]]\n[[Category:First Nations in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Communities in Kings County, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mi'kmaq governments]]\n", "name_user": "2605:b100:d37:5ec1:87cd:e99e:f847:df12", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFinancial controversies)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glooscap_First_Nation"}
{"title_page": "407 Proxy Authentication Required (Mr. Robot)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = 407 Proxy Authentication Required\n| series         = [[Mr. Robot]]\n| image          = <!-- bare filename only. Wikilinking, \"File:\", and pixel size not required. -->\n| image_size     = <!-- raw number. \"px\" not required. -->\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 4\n| episode        = 7\n| director       = [[Sam Esmail]]\n| writer         = Sam Esmail\n| producer       = \n| music          = \n| photographer   = \n| editor         = \n| production     = \n| airdate        = {{Start date|2019|11|17}}\n| length         = 56 minutes\n| awards         = \n| guests         = *[[Gloria Reuben]] as Krista Gordon\n*[[Young M.A]] as Peanuts\n*Jahneer E. Williams as Javi\n| prev           = [[406 Not Acceptable (Mr. Robot)|406 Not Acceptable]]\n| next           = [[408 Request Timeout (Mr. Robot)|408 Request Timeout]]\n| season_article = \n| episode_list   = List of Mr. Robot episodes\n}}\n\n\"'''407 Proxy Authentication Required'''\" is the seventh episode of the fourth season of the American [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] [[drama]] television series ''[[Mr. Robot]],'' and the 39th episode overall. Written and directed by series creator [[Sam Esmail]], it aired on November 17, 2019, on [[USA Network]].\n\nIn the episode, Elliot Alderson ([[Rami Malek]]) and his therapist Krista Gordon ([[Gloria Reuben]]) are held hostage by Fernando Vera ([[Elliot Villar]]), who attempts to coerce Elliot into working alongside him by understanding Mr. Robot. \n\nThe episode received critical acclaim, with many naming it as one of the best of the entire series. Particular praise was directed at Malek{{r|AV Club rev}} and Villar's{{r|NYT-rev}} performances, as well as Esmail's direction and writing. For the episode, Esmail received a nomination for [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama|Best Episodic Drama]] at the [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2019|72nd Writers Guild of America Awards]].\n\n== Plot ==\n{{Plot|episode|date=December 2019}}\nFollowing the events of [[List of Mr. Robot episodes#ep38|the previous episode]], Elliot is kidnapped by Vera and his associates Peanut and Javi. He is removed from the boot of a car and then tied to a chair in a room adjacent to Krista, who is also being held hostage.\n\nVera recounts his life after the events of \"[[List of Mr. Robot episodes#ep6|eps1.5_br4ve-trave1er.asf]]\", having returned to the [[Dominican Republic]]. He describes his journey from street hustling to taking control of the country as well as [[Haiti]] in 87 days. On day 88 however, his inscrutable feelings of emptiness are vindicated by a [[Shamanism|shaman]] who tells him he must return home. Realizing his desire to return to New York to reconcile with Elliot, he states his plan to take over New York with Elliot as his business partner. Elliot, remembering Shayla's death at Vera's hands, refuses to cooperate without Krista's safety guaranteed. \n\nElliot is brought to Krista and shown that she is safe. Vera reveals his knowledge of Mr. Robot, having extracted it from Krista, and declares his desire to meet him. Mr. Robot takes control after Krista is threatened. He points out flaws in Vera's plan, but offers to help if Krista is let go. Vera protests the suggestion, stating that Krista's captivity guarantees Elliot's cooperation. Elliot offers Vera the money from the Cyprus Bank hack he is planning.\n\nVera and his crew view the hack's details on a laptop. Seeing they are distracted, Elliot grabs for a gun in his bag. He threatens to shoot Vera and pulls the trigger, but realizes that the gun had already been unloaded. Angered, Vera threatens to shoot Krista, until Elliot admits that he needs her. Vera, comparing her to the shaman that had helped him, decides to change his approach.\n\nVera forces Krista and Elliot into an impromptu therapy session to discover more about Mr. Robot. Krista protests, saying it will not work without a controlled and private environment. Vera orders his associates to leave. Krista, still not satisfied, acquiesces after convincing from Elliot. Growing impatient with the discussion of Elliot's mother, Vera demands they discuss the origins of Mr. Robot's existence. Elliot begins to feel that a secret is being kept from him. Frustrated by Mr. Robot and Krista's attempts at diverting the subject matter, he encourages Vera to read from Krista's files. The window event from his childhood is brought up as a moment of significance. Elliot's version of events, that he swung a bat at his father and then jumped out of a window in a state of mania, is called into question after Krista points out Elliot's reliance on Darlene's memories and not his own. Krista compares his poor memory of the day to his inability to remember moments where Mr. Robot takes control. Elliot realizes Mr. Robot took control that day, having existed for longer than he had thought. Krista questions Mr. Robot's purpose, and puts together the pieces that Elliot needed protecting, specifically from his father. He finally remembers that he was sexually abused by his father as a child as he breaks down.\n\nUnable to come to terms with his abuse, Elliot is consoled by Vera. Elliot blames Vera for the revelation. Vera then reveals his own past with sexual abuse, from friends of his mother. Vera says people with their trauma should not struggle alone, and confides his philosophy that people like them become unstoppable. After Vera assures Elliot that he isn't alone anymore, Krista, sneaking up, stabs Vera in the back. Vera dies from his wounds, as Elliot and Krista escape.\n\n== Production ==\nThe episode is presented in a five-act structure which critics compared to resembling the structure of a [[Play (theatre)|play]],{{r|IBT}} emphasized by its reliance on dramatic audio cues and usage of two adjacent sets. It was also broadcast on [[USA Network]] commercial-free, and featured crisis resource information for viewers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/mr-robot-recap-season-4-episode-7.html |title=Mr. Robot Recap: You Become the Storm |last=Murthi |first=Vikram |date=November 17, 2019 |website=Vulture |language=en-us|access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe episode received universal acclaim from critics and audiences. The episode has a 100% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with an average score of 9.3/10.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mr. Robot - Season 4 Episode 7 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/mr_robot/s04/e07 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> Special attention was given to Malek's performance, Esmail's direction, and cinematography.{{r|NYT-rev}} ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the show's courage and \"high risk, high reward\" storytelling of asking the audience to wrestle with something horrific right at the root of the show.{{r|NYT-rev}} ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' declared the episode among the series' finest episodes and a potent statement of purpose from Esmail.{{r|AV Club rev}} ''[[TVLine]]'' named Malek their \"Performer of the Week\" for his performance in the episode, stating \"It's the heaviest moment we've seen so far on the series, a true game-changer, and Malek played every difficult note of it with astounding precision\" and that \"Malek has added another layer to a truly unforgettable performance.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/11/23/rami-malek-mr-robot-season-4-episode-7-performance/ |title=Performer of the Week: Rami Malek |work=TVLine |date=November 23, 2019 |accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSam Esmail received a nomination for [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama|Best Episodic Drama]] at the [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2019|72nd Writers Guild of America Awards]] for the episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/wga-tv-nominees-watchmen-russian-doll-veep-succession-1202194635 |title=Writers Guild Awards 2019: \u2018Watchmen,\u2019 \u2018PEN15\u2019 Among TV Nominees |work=Indiewire |first=Libby |last=Hill |date=December 5, 2019 |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn its initial broadcast on USA Network on November 17, 2019, the episode received 361,000 viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-17-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.17.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=November 19, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"AV Club rev\">{{Cite web |last1=McLevy |first1=Alex |title=All the scales drop as Mr. Robot delivers one of its finest episodes ever |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=November 17, 2019 |url=https://tv.avclub.com/all-the-scales-drop-as-mr-robot-delivers-one-of-its-fi-1839908814 |language=en-us |accessdate=November 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=IBT>{{Cite web |last1=Fox |first1=Kasey |title='Mr. Robot' Recap: Explaining The Most Tragic Episode Yet |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/mr-robot-recap-explaining-most-tragic-episode-yet-2868681 |accessdate=November 29, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NYT-rev>{{Cite news |last1=Collins |first1=Sean T. |title=\u2018Mr. Robot\u2019 Season 4, Episode 7: Acts of Malice |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 17, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/17/arts/television/mr-robot-episode-7-recap.html |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Fowle |first1=Kyle |title='Mr. Robot' recap: Elliot's world crumbles |work=[[EW.com]] |date=November 17, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/recap/mr-robot-season-4-episode-7/ |language=en |accessdate=November 19, 2019 }}\n* {{Cite web |last1=Grauer |first1=Yael |title=Hackers Dissect 'Mr. Robot' Season 4 Episode 7: \u2018Proxy Authentication Required\u2019 |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/a35m4z/hackers-dissect-mr-robot-season-4-episode-7-proxy-authentication-required |language=en |accessdate=November 19, 2019 }}\n* {{Cite web |last1=Wigler |first1=Josh |title='Mr. Robot' Final Season Delivers the Drama's Most Devastating Moment Yet in Ad-Free Episode |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=November 17, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/mr-robot-final-season-episode-seven-407-proxy-authentication-required-explained-1255540 |language=en |accessdate=November 29, 2019 }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.usanetwork.com/mrrobot/episode-guide/season-4-episode-7-407-proxy-authentication-required \"407 Proxy Authentication Required\"] at [[USA Network]]\n* {{IMDb episode|8084176}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:407 Proxy Authentication Required (''Mr. Robot'')}}\n{{Mr. Robot}}\n[[Category:Mr. Robot episodes]]\n[[Category:2019 American television episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = 407 Proxy Authentication Required\n| series         = [[Mr. Robot]]\n| image          = <!-- bare filename only. Wikilinking, \"File:\", and pixel size not required. -->\n| image_size     = <!-- raw number. \"px\" not required. -->\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 4\n| episode        = 7\n| director       = [[Sam Esmail]]\n| writer         = Sam Esmail\n| producer       = \n| music          = \n| photographer   = \n| editor         = \n| production     = \n| airdate        = {{Start date|2019|11|17}}\n| length         = 56 minutes\n| awards         = \n| guests         = *[[Gloria Reuben]] as Krista Gordon\n*[[Young M.A]] as Peanuts\n*Jahneer E. Williams as Javi\n| prev           = [[406 Not Acceptable (Mr. Robot)|406 Not Acceptable]]\n| next           = [[408 Request Timeout (Mr. Robot)|408 Request Timeout]]\n| season_article = \n| episode_list   = List of Mr. Robot episodes\n}}\n\n\"'''407 Proxy Authentication Required'''\" is the seventh episode of the fourth season of the American [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] [[drama]] television series ''[[Mr. Robot]],'' and the 39th episode overall. Written and directed by series creator [[Sam Esmail]], it aired on November 17, 2019, on [[USA Network]].\n\nIn the episode, Elliot Alderson ([[Rami Malek]]) and his therapist Krista Gordon ([[Gloria Reuben]]) are held hostage by Fernando Vera ([[Elliot Villar]]), who attempts to coerce Elliot into working alongside him by understanding Mr. Robot. \n\nThe episode received critical acclaim, with many naming it as one of the best of the entire series. Particular praise was directed at Malek{{r|AV Club rev}} and Villar's{{r|NYT-rev}} performances, as well as Esmail's direction and writing. For the episode, Esmail received a nomination for [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama|Best Episodic Drama]] at the [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2019|72nd Writers Guild of America Awards]].\n\n== Plot ==\n{{Plot|episode|date=December 2019}}\nFollowing the events of [[List of Mr. Robot episodes#ep38|the previous episode]], Elliot is kidnapped by Vera and his associates Peanut and Javi. He is removed from the boot of a car and then tied to a chair in a room adjacent to Krista, who is also being held hostage.\n\nVera recounts his life after the events of \"[[List of Mr. Robot episodes#ep6|eps1.5_br4ve-trave1er.asf]]\", having returned to the [[Dominican Republic]]. He describes his journey from street hustling to taking control of the country as well as [[Haiti]] in 87 days. On day 88 however, his inscrutable feelings of emptiness are vindicated by a [[Shamanism|shaman]] who tells him