{"title_page": "Spiral (2020 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|Upcoming horror film directed by Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Spiral: From The Book of Saw\n| image          = Spiral (2020) poster.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Teaser poster with original release date\n| director       = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Josh Stolberg]]\n* Peter Goldfinger\n}}\n| story          = [[Chris Rock]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Saw (franchise)|Saw]]''|[[James Wan]]|[[Leigh Whannell]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Chris Rock\n* [[Samuel L. Jackson]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = Jordan Oram<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hnentertainment.co/new-rumor-suggests-spider-man-far-from-home-star-samuel-l-jackson-has-joined-chris-rocks-saw-reboot/ |title=Update: 'Spider-Man: Far From Home' Star Samuel L. Jackson Has Joined Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=Marc |first=Christopher |website=HN Entertainment |date=July 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| editing        = Dev Singh<ref>{{cite web |last=Singh |first=Dev |title=Dev Singh Biography |url=https://www.dgc.ca/en/national/the-guild/leaders/national-directors-division/memberView?m=22606 |website=Directors Guild of Canada |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] (United States)\n* [[Mongrel Media]] (Canada)\n}}\n| released       = \n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Spiral: From The Book of Saw''''', or simply '''''Spiral''''', is an upcoming American [[horror film|horror]] film. The film will serve as the ninth installment in the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' film series]]. It was directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], and written by [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger. The film stars [[Chris Rock]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Max Minghella]], and [[Marisol Nichols]].\n\nThe film was originally scheduled to be released in the United States on May 15, 2020, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]], but due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the film was temporarily removed from the release schedule.<ref name=\"Reschedule\">{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/new-saw-movie-spiral-antebellum-release-date-delayed-coronavirus/ |title=Lionsgate Delays Chris Rock's 'Saw' Movie, Janelle Monae's 'Antebellum' |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nLionsgate's officially released synopsis reads \"Working in the shadow of an esteemed police veteran ([[Samuel L. Jackson]]), brash detective Ezekiel \"Zeke\" Banks ([[Chris Rock]]) and his rookie partner William Schenk ([[Max Minghella]]) take charge of a grisly investigation into murders that are eerily reminiscent of the city's gruesome past. Unwittingly trapped in a deepening mystery, Zeke finds himself at the center of the killer's morbid game.\"<ref name=\"Patches\"/>\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Chris Rock]] as Det. Ezekiel \"Zeke\" Banks\n* [[Samuel L. Jackson]] as Marcus\n* [[Max Minghella]] as Det. William Schenk<ref name=\"thewrap\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/samuel-l-jackson-joins-chris-rocks-saw-reboot/ |title=Samuel L. Jackson Joins Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=Welk |first=Brian |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=July 8, 2019 |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Marisol Nichols]] as Capt. Angie Garza<ref name=\"thewrap\"/>\n* [[Zoie Palmer]] as Kara Boswick\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAccording to [[Chris Rock]], the origins of ''Spiral: From The Book of Saw'' came from a chance meeting with the head of [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] at a friend's wedding, and felt doing something in the horror genre would be a new avenue to take his career, though planned to include some comedic elements in the film.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://collider.com/why-chris-rock-made-a-saw-movie/ | title = Chris Rock Explains Why He Made a 'Saw' Movie | first = Adam | last =Chitwood | date = January 13, 2020 | accessdate = January 22, 2020 | work = [[Collider (website)|Collider]] }}</ref>  Rock approached Lionsgate with his ideas of extending the franchise, who became very interested in the concept.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/chris-rock-to-reboot-saw-franchise-with-lionsgate-twisted-pictures-1202616185/ |title=Chris Rock To Reboot 'Saw' Franchise With Lionsgate & Twisted Pictures |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Lionsgate's CEO [[Joe Drake (producer)|Joe Drake]] said that Rock's idea was \"completely reverential to the legacy of the material while reinvigorating the brand with his wit, creative vision and passion for this classic horror franchise\".<ref name=\"announce\"/> By January 2018, industry rumors had said that Lionsgate had begun discussions of a ninth ''Saw'' film, for which [[The Spierig Brothers]] would not be returning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-jigsaw-sequel/ |title='Saw 9' Conversation is Reportedly Happening |last=Stephens |first=David |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet, Inc. |date=January 16, 2018 |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> By April 2018, [[Twisted Pictures]] was reported to be developing a sequel with ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'' writers [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3491755/jigsaw-writers-currently-working-next-saw-exclusive/ |title='Jigsaw' Writers Are Currently Working On Next 'Saw' [Exclusive] |last=Miska |first=Brad |date=April 3, 2018 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2019, the film was officially in production.<ref name=\"announce\"/> Former series director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] returned to helm the film, along with series veterans [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] as producers. Rock was involved as an executive producer, in addition to writing the story treatment. Joining Rock as executive producers included the original ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' creators [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]], along with Daniel Heffner.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3561412/saw-reimagined-chris-rock-darren-bousman-returning-direct/ |title='Saw' Being Reimagined by Chris Rock with Darren Bousman Returning to Direct! |first=Brad |last=Miska |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Stolberg and Goldfinger were affirmed as scriptwriters.<ref name=\"announce\"/> With the announcement, Rock stated, \"I've been a fan of ''Saw'' since the first film in 2004. I am excited by the opportunity to take this to a really intense and twisted new place.\"<ref name=\"announce\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/chris-rock-saw-spinoff-1203216731/ | title = Chris Rock Rebooting 'Saw' Franchise With Lionsgate | first=  Dave | last =  McNary | date = May 16, 2019 | accessdate = July 8, 2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | publisher = [[Penske Media Corporation]] }}</ref> Burg and Koules said that Rock's treatment of ''Saw'' was comparable to what [[Eddie Murphy]] had done for [[buddy cop film]]s in ''[[48 Hrs.]]'', giving the ''Saw'' series a \"completely fresh perspective\".<ref name=\"announce\"/> Stolberg later confirmed that the ninth installment will exist in the same canon as the previous eight films, and will not be a reboot, nor will it be a direct sequel to ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a28205256/saw-movie-reboot-timeline-confirmed/ | title = How 'Saw' reboot fits in with the series timeline | first= Dan | last = Seddon | date = July 8, 2019 | accessdate = July 8, 2019 | work = [[Digital Spy]] | publisher = [[Hearst Communications]]}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nOn July 8, 2019, filming commenced in [[Toronto]] under the working title of ''The Organ Donor''. Rock, [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Max Minghella]], and [[Marisol Nichols]] were announced to be starring in the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/samuel-l-jackson-chris-rock-saw-movie-1203260924/ |title=Samuel L. Jackson to Star in Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=July 8, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-movie-filming-start/ |title=New 'Saw' Movie Set To Start Filming This Month |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet, Inc. |first=Q. V. |last=Hough |date=June 27, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Lionsgate's CEO Joe Drake stated, \"We think Samuel L. Jackson and Chris Rock along with Max Minghella and Marisol Nichols make this film completely special in the ''Saw'' canon and we can't wait to unleash this unexpected and sinister new story on fans of this franchise. This is next level of ''Saw'' on full tilt.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/more-like-saw-muel-l-jackson-right-1836185124?IR=T |title=More Like Saw-muel L. Jackson, Right? |last=Lussier |first=Germain |date=July 9, 2019 |website=[[Gizmodo]] |publisher=[[G/O Media]] |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> On August 28, 2019, filming officially wrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3580945/chris-rocks-new-take-saw-wraps-production/ |title=Chris Rock's New Take on 'Saw' Wraps Production |last=Brad |first=Miska |date=August 28, 2019 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref> In February 2020, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] gave the film an R rating, for \"sequences of grisly bloody violence and torture, pervasive language, some sexual references and brief drug use\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.filmratings.com/Search?filmTitle=spiral&x=0&y=0| title=Spiral (2020) | work=The Classification and Rating Adiministration | publisher=[[Motion Picture Association of America]] | accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nThe film was known under the working title ''The Organ Donor''<ref>{{cite web |last=Wilhelmi |first=Jack|title=How Does The 'Saw' Reboot Connect To The Original Movies? |url=https://screenrant.com/how-the-saw-reboot-connects-to-original-movies/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |date=November 24, 2019 |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> until the name ''Spiral: From the Book of Saw'' was leaked to the press on January 22, 2020, along with [[Mongrel Media]] as the Canadian distributor.<ref>{{cite web |last=Burwick |first=Kevin |title=Bewildering Saw 9 Title Allegedly Leaks, But Is It for Real? |url=https://movieweb.com/saw-9-official-title-spiral/ |website=[[MovieWeb]] |date=January 22, 2020 |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The first teaser poster and trailer, released on February 5, 2020, confirmed ''Spiral'' as the title of the film.<ref name=\"Patches\">{{cite web |last=Patches |first= Matt |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/5/21124064/spiral-trailer-chris-rock-saw-reboot|title=The 'Spiral' trailer is our first cut of Chris Rock's Saw reboot|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate = February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Spiral'' was originally scheduled to be released on October 23, 2020, but was moved up to May 15, 2020, to avoid competition with ''[[Halloween Kills]]'', the sequel to 2018's ''[[Halloween (2018 film)|Halloween]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/chris-rock-saw-reboot-may-2020-1203275353/ |title=Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot Moves Up Five Months to May 2020 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref> The film was delayed a second time as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. Lionsgate intends to announce a new release date once its known that theaters can safely reopen.<ref name=\"Reschedule\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.lionsgate.com/movies/spiral}}\n* {{IMDb title|10342730|Spiral}}\n* [http://www.mongrelmedia.com/index.php/filmlink?id=66364d59-dfc5-e911-a98f-0edcbcd33718  ''Spiral''] on [[Mongrel Media]]\n\n{{Chris Rock}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Saw}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spiral (2020 film)}}\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Saw films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming sequel films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Upcoming horror film directed by Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Spiral: From The Book of Saw\n| image          = Spiral (2020) poster.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Teaser poster with original release date\n| director       = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Josh Stolberg]]\n* Peter Goldfinger\n}}\n| story          = [[Chris Rock]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Saw (franchise)|Saw]]''|[[James Wan]]|[[Leigh Whannell]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Chris Rock\n* [[Samuel L. Jackson]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = Jordan Oram<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hnentertainment.co/new-rumor-suggests-spider-man-far-from-home-star-samuel-l-jackson-has-joined-chris-rocks-saw-reboot/ |title=Update: 'Spider-Man: Far From Home' Star Samuel L. Jackson Has Joined Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=Marc |first=Christopher |website=HN Entertainment |date=July 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| editing        = Dev Singh<ref>{{cite web |last=Singh |first=Dev |title=Dev Singh Biography |url=https://www.dgc.ca/en/national/the-guild/leaders/national-directors-division/memberView?m=22606 |website=Directors Guild of Canada |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] (United States)\n* [[Mongrel Media]] (Canada)\n}}\n| released       = \n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Spiral: From The Book of Saw''''', or simply '''''Spiral''''', is an upcoming American [[horror film|horror]] film. The film will serve as the ninth installment in the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' franchise]]. It was directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], and written by [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger. The film stars [[Chris Rock]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Max Minghella]], and [[Marisol Nichols]].\n\nThe film was originally scheduled to be released in the United States on May 15, 2020, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]], but due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the film was temporarily removed from the release schedule.<ref name=\"Reschedule\">{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/new-saw-movie-spiral-antebellum-release-date-delayed-coronavirus/ |title=Lionsgate Delays Chris Rock's 'Saw' Movie, Janelle Monae's 'Antebellum' |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nLionsgate's officially released synopsis reads \"Working in the shadow of an esteemed police veteran ([[Samuel L. Jackson]]), brash detective Ezekiel \"Zeke\" Banks ([[Chris Rock]]) and his rookie partner William Schenk ([[Max Minghella]]) take charge of a grisly investigation into murders that are eerily reminiscent of the city's gruesome past. Unwittingly trapped in a deepening mystery, Zeke finds himself at the center of the killer's morbid game.\"<ref name=\"Patches\"/>\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Chris Rock]] as Det. Ezekiel \"Zeke\" Banks\n* [[Samuel L. Jackson]] as Marcus\n* [[Max Minghella]] as Det. William Schenk<ref name=\"thewrap\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/samuel-l-jackson-joins-chris-rocks-saw-reboot/ |title=Samuel L. Jackson Joins Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=Welk |first=Brian |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=July 8, 2019 |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Marisol Nichols]] as Capt. Angie Garza<ref name=\"thewrap\"/>\n* [[Zoie Palmer]] as Kara Boswick\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAccording to [[Chris Rock]], the origins of ''Spiral: From The Book of Saw'' came from a chance meeting with the head of [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] at a friend's wedding, and felt doing something in the horror genre would be a new avenue to take his career, though planned to include some comedic elements in the film.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://collider.com/why-chris-rock-made-a-saw-movie/ | title = Chris Rock Explains Why He Made a 'Saw' Movie | first = Adam | last =Chitwood | date = January 13, 2020 | accessdate = January 22, 2020 | work = [[Collider (website)|Collider]] }}</ref>  Rock approached Lionsgate with his ideas of extending the franchise, who became very interested in the concept.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/chris-rock-to-reboot-saw-franchise-with-lionsgate-twisted-pictures-1202616185/ |title=Chris Rock To Reboot 'Saw' Franchise With Lionsgate & Twisted Pictures |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Lionsgate's CEO [[Joe Drake (producer)|Joe Drake]] said that Rock's idea was \"completely reverential to the legacy of the material while reinvigorating the brand with his wit, creative vision and passion for this classic horror franchise\".<ref name=\"announce\"/> By January 2018, industry rumors had said that Lionsgate had begun discussions of a ninth ''Saw'' film, for which [[The Spierig Brothers]] would not be returning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-jigsaw-sequel/ |title='Saw 9' Conversation is Reportedly Happening |last=Stephens |first=David |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet, Inc. |date=January 16, 2018 |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> By April 2018, [[Twisted Pictures]] was reported to be developing a sequel with ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'' writers [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3491755/jigsaw-writers-currently-working-next-saw-exclusive/ |title='Jigsaw' Writers Are Currently Working On Next 'Saw' [Exclusive] |last=Miska |first=Brad |date=April 3, 2018 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2019, the film was officially in production.<ref name=\"announce\"/> Former series director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] returned to helm the film, along with series veterans [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] as producers. Rock was involved as an executive producer, in addition to writing the story treatment. Joining Rock as executive producers included the original ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' creators [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]], along with Daniel Heffner.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3561412/saw-reimagined-chris-rock-darren-bousman-returning-direct/ |title='Saw' Being Reimagined by Chris Rock with Darren Bousman Returning to Direct! |first=Brad |last=Miska |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Stolberg and Goldfinger were affirmed as scriptwriters.<ref name=\"announce\"/> With the announcement, Rock stated, \"I've been a fan of ''Saw'' since the first film in 2004. I am excited by the opportunity to take this to a really intense and twisted new place.\"<ref name=\"announce\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/chris-rock-saw-spinoff-1203216731/ | title = Chris Rock Rebooting 'Saw' Franchise With Lionsgate | first=  Dave | last =  McNary | date = May 16, 2019 | accessdate = July 8, 2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | publisher = [[Penske Media Corporation]] }}</ref> Burg and Koules said that Rock's treatment of ''Saw'' was comparable to what [[Eddie Murphy]] had done for [[buddy cop film]]s in ''[[48 Hrs.]]'', giving the ''Saw'' series a \"completely fresh perspective\".<ref name=\"announce\"/> Stolberg later confirmed that the ninth installment will exist in the same canon as the previous eight films, and will not be a reboot, nor will it be a direct sequel to ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a28205256/saw-movie-reboot-timeline-confirmed/ | title = How 'Saw' reboot fits in with the series timeline | first= Dan | last = Seddon | date = July 8, 2019 | accessdate = July 8, 2019 | work = [[Digital Spy]] | publisher = [[Hearst Communications]]}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nOn July 8, 2019, filming commenced in [[Toronto]] under the working title of ''The Organ Donor''. Rock, [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Max Minghella]], and [[Marisol Nichols]] were announced to be starring in the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/samuel-l-jackson-chris-rock-saw-movie-1203260924/ |title=Samuel L. Jackson to Star in Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=July 8, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-movie-filming-start/ |title=New 'Saw' Movie Set To Start Filming This Month |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet, Inc. |first=Q. V. |last=Hough |date=June 27, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Lionsgate's CEO Joe Drake stated, \"We think Samuel L. Jackson and Chris Rock along with Max Minghella and Marisol Nichols make this film completely special in the ''Saw'' canon and we can't wait to unleash this unexpected and sinister new story on fans of this franchise. This is next level of ''Saw'' on full tilt.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/more-like-saw-muel-l-jackson-right-1836185124?IR=T |title=More Like Saw-muel L. Jackson, Right? |last=Lussier |first=Germain |date=July 9, 2019 |website=[[Gizmodo]] |publisher=[[G/O Media]] |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> On August 28, 2019, filming officially wrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3580945/chris-rocks-new-take-saw-wraps-production/ |title=Chris Rock's New Take on 'Saw' Wraps Production |last=Brad |first=Miska |date=August 28, 2019 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref> In February 2020, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] gave the film an R rating, for \"sequences of grisly bloody violence and torture, pervasive language, some sexual references and brief drug use\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.filmratings.com/Search?filmTitle=spiral&x=0&y=0| title=Spiral (2020) | work=The Classification and Rating Adiministration | publisher=[[Motion Picture Association of America]] | accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nThe film was known under the working title ''The Organ Donor''<ref>{{cite web |last=Wilhelmi |first=Jack|title=How Does The 'Saw' Reboot Connect To The Original Movies? |url=https://screenrant.com/how-the-saw-reboot-connects-to-original-movies/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |date=November 24, 2019 |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> until the name ''Spiral: From the Book of Saw'' was leaked to the press on January 22, 2020, along with [[Mongrel Media]] as the Canadian distributor.<ref>{{cite web |last=Burwick |first=Kevin |title=Bewildering Saw 9 Title Allegedly Leaks, But Is It for Real? |url=https://movieweb.com/saw-9-official-title-spiral/ |website=[[MovieWeb]] |date=January 22, 2020 |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The first teaser poster and trailer, released on February 5, 2020, confirmed ''Spiral'' as the title of the film.<ref name=\"Patches\">{{cite web |last=Patches |first= Matt |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/5/21124064/spiral-trailer-chris-rock-saw-reboot|title=The 'Spiral' trailer is our first cut of Chris Rock's Saw reboot|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate = February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Spiral'' was originally scheduled to be released on October 23, 2020, but was moved up to May 15, 2020, to avoid competition with ''[[Halloween Kills]]'', the sequel to 2018's ''[[Halloween (2018 film)|Halloween]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/chris-rock-saw-reboot-may-2020-1203275353/ |title=Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot Moves Up Five Months to May 2020 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref> The film was delayed a second time as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. Lionsgate intends to announce a new release date once its known that theaters can safely reopen.<ref name=\"Reschedule\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.lionsgate.com/movies/spiral}}\n* {{IMDb title|10342730|Spiral}}\n* [http://www.mongrelmedia.com/index.php/filmlink?id=66364d59-dfc5-e911-a98f-0edcbcd33718  ''Spiral''] on [[Mongrel Media]]\n\n{{Chris Rock}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Saw}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spiral (2020 film)}}\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Saw films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming sequel films]]\n", "name_user": "Acekard", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiral_(2020_film)"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Hamilton (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name            = Alexander Hamilton\n| artist          = [[Leslie Odom Jr.]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]], [[Daveed Diggs]], [[Okieriete Onaodowan]], [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], [[Phillipa Soo]], [[Christopher Jackson (actor)|Christopher Jackson]], & the Cast of ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]''\n| album           = [[Hamilton (album)|Hamilton]]\n| released        = 2015\n| recorded        = \n| genre           = \n*[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n*[[show tune]]\n| length          = 3:56\n| writer          = [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Alexander Hamilton'''\" is the opening number for the 2015 musical ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'', a musical biography of American [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Founding Father]] [[Alexander Hamilton]], which premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 2015. [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]] wrote both the music and lyrics to the song. This song features \"alternately rapped and sung exposition\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/hamilton-an-american-musical-original-broadway-cast-recording-mw0002869830|title=Hamilton: An American Musical [Original Broadway Cast Recording]|first=Marcy|last=Donelson|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lin Manuel Miranda White House Poetry Jam 2009.webm|thumb|thumbtime=3:37|left|Lin-Manuel Miranda performs an early version of the song at the White House poetry jam in 2009.|alt=Lin-Manuel Miranda performs an early version of ''Alexander Hamilton'' at the White House Poetry Jam]]\nThis song was originally part of a group of songs entitled \"The Hamilton Mixtape\" and created by [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]] as he started interpreting and adapting  [[Ron Chernow]]'s ''Hamilton'' biography for the stage. He performed this number live at a White House poetry jam in 2009. The ''[[National Review]]'' noted \"The [[Obama family|Obamas]] and the other guests react with more than a touch of surprise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/nrd/articles/415685/funky-founder|title=National Review Online|date=6 April 2015|work=National Review Online}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' writes that \"Miranda later heard that [[Barack Obama|the President's]] first reaction was to remark that [[Timothy Geithner]] had to see this.\"<ref name=\"rebeccamead\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/02/09/hamiltons|title=Hip-Hop Hamilton \u2013 The New Yorker|first=Rebecca|last=Mead|date=9 February 2015|work=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref> The musical, and this song's YouTube video in particular, have influenced education; Miranda said \"I think teachers used just that one clip for the past six years as their intro to Hamilton.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Zach|last=Schonfeld|url=http://www.newsweek.com/hamilton-biggest-thing-broadway-being-taught-classrooms-all-over-424212|title='Hamilton' Biggest Thing Broadway Being Taught Classrooms All Over|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|date=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the song was performed live at the [[Grammy]]s, the first time a song was broadcast live from a Broadway stage for the Hollywood award show. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said they \"wowed\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6875296/hamilton-2016-grammys-performance|title=Hamilton Cast's 2016 Grammys Performance: Alexander Hamilton \u2013 Video \u2013 Billboard|work=Billboard}}</ref> while [[TV Line]] deemed it \"crowd-pleasing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/02/15/hamilton-grammys-2016-video-alexander-performance/|title=[VIDEO] 'Hamilton' Cast Performs 'Alexander Hamilton' at Grammys 2016 \u2013 TVLine|first=Kimberly|last=Roots|work=[[TVLine]]}}</ref> ''Billboard'' deemed it the night's fourth best live musical moment, writing \"the emotional, enervating retelling of American history was one of the night's standout moments\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6875385/2016-grammys-performances-ranked|title=2016 Grammys Performances Ranked From Worst to Best|work=Billboard}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' also deemed it a highlight and wrote \"It's not Hamilton's most compelling set piece, but it's a very solid introduction to the show's characters, cast and themes. For millions that won't be able to make it to Broadway this year, watching it performed on network TV was the next best thing to actually scoring a ticket.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/grammys-2016-20-best-and-worst-moments-224720/amp/|title=Grammys 2016: 20 Best and Worst Moments|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nThis song is explanatory, setting up who the main character is and summarizing the first two decades of his life in a \"bracingly economical synopsis of Hamilton's early years\".<ref name=\"pitchfork.com\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21122-hamilton-original-broadway-cast-recording/|title=Various Artists|work=Pitchfork}}</ref> It also introduces the other major characters of [[Aaron Burr]], [[John Laurens]], [[Thomas Jefferson]], [[James Madison]], [[Elizabeth Schuyler Hamilton|Eliza Schuyler Hamilton]], [[George Washington]], [[Hercules Mulligan]], [[Marquis de Lafayette]], [[Angelica Schuyler Church]], and [[Maria Reynolds]], and briefly describes Hamilton's relationships to many of them. This \"prologue\" to the story, according to [[Patheos]], \"doesn't just bring Hamilton to life, but all of his contemporaries as well\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/moniqueocampowrites/2015/10/14/hamilton-the-musical-an-album-review/|title=Hamilton The Musical: An Album Review|work=Monique Ocampo Writes}}</ref>\n\nThe derogatory terms used in the number to describe Hamilton, including \"bastard\", \"orphan\", \"son of a whore and a Scotsman\" are repeated throughout the musical in  a motif that demonstrates how his upbringing would haunt him for the rest of his life, despite his attempt to escape his childhood misfortunes and climb to the top of the social ladder. This term was \"derived from a contemptuous description by [[John Adams]]\".<ref name=\"rebeccamead\"/>\n\nFor over two centuries both Hamilton and Burr have been well-known for [[Burr\u2013Hamilton duel|their infamous duel]], in which Burr fatally shot Hamilton. In the opening number, Burr himself acknowledges this, essentially giving away the ending. Thus, like the musical ''[[Titanic (musical)|Titanic]]'', the story becomes more about the journey than the destination.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\">{{cite web|first=Elizabeth|last=Logan|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/elizabeth-logan/i-have-an-opinion-on-ever_b_8223496.html|title=I Have an Opinion on Every Song in \"Hamilton\"|date=1 October 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==Analysis==\n''[[The Atlantic]]'' notes that the musical's opening question \"How does a bastard, orphan, son of a whore and a Scotsman, dropped in the middle of a forgotten spot in the Caribbean by providence, impoverished, in squalor grow up to be a hero and a scholar?\" is answered throughout the following two acts, and essentially becomes \"relentless labor\", epitomised in Burr's rise to power, Hamilton's written documents, and Eliza's securing of Hamilton's legacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/hamilton-cast-album-best-album-of-2015/420975/|title=Why the 'Hamilton' Cast Recording Is the Best Album of 2015 \u2013 The Atlantic|first=Spencer|last=Kornhaber|work=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\nUloop argues that Burr is actually ''Hamilton's'' main character, writing that in this opening number \"Lin portrays his Burr as one completely knowing of his crime to come, in the style of ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]''{{'}}s [[Judas]], and with the ferocity of ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis]]''{{'}} [[Javert]].\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Trevor|last=Dunham|url=http://fsu.uloop.com/news/view.php/172609/hamilton-album-review-starting-a-revolution-pt-2|title=Hamilton Album Review: Starting a Revolution Pt. 2|work=Uloop|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:US10dollarbill-Series 2004A.jpg|thumb|The US Treasury canceled plans to replace \"the ten-dollar Founding Father\" on the [[United States ten-dollar bill|ten-dollar bill]] in part because fans of the ''Hamilton'' musical opposed the change.<ref>{{cite news | last = Viagas | first = Robert | title = It's Official: Alexander Hamilton Will Stay on $10 Bill | magazine = [[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]] | date = April 20, 2016 | url = http://www.playbill.com/article/treasury-secretary-to-announce-today-that-hamilton-will-stay-on-10-bill-com-351602 | quote = U.S. Treasury Secretary Jacob J. Lew announced April 20 that founding Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton's portrait will remain on the front of the $10 bill . . . . Fans of the Broadway musical ''Hamilton'' had clamored to keep the man described in the show as the 'ten-dollar Founding Father' on the note.}}</ref>]]\nThe song has received critical acclaim.  ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' argues that the song's wordplay and self-awareness elevates it above other opening numbers that rely on this \"sung exposition\" technique.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/> [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] explains that the song sets the musical tone by incorporating rap while being \"still essentially in musical-theater territory\".<ref name=\"pitchfork.com\"/> With Burr acting as the narrator of this number, ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' comments: \"fitting, somehow, that the man who jealously slew Hamilton in a duel is the first to take up the mystery of his story\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-cm-hamilton-hip-hop-notebook-20151031-column.html|title=Review: 'Hamilton' is a watershed musical that sets a Founding Father's tale to hip-hop|first=Charles |last=McNulty|date=4 November 2015|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]'', rapper [[Talib Kweli]] effusively praised the song as an exemplar of hip-hop, saying, \"My heart swelled with pride after I heard this song, because I was like, 'This right here is hip-hop.' Hip-hop has no boundaries and no limits, and Lin-Manuel and his crew are proving it\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Loretta|last=Charlton|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/10/talib-kweli-analyzes-hamilton.html|title=Talib Kweli Analyzes Hamilton|work=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Ricordia]] described it as \"the anthem of a man that changed the world\", and argued it should be the anthem of all listeners too.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmaricordia.com/2147/entertainment/hamilton-soundtrack-review/#sthash.jCE0eTnI.dpuf|title=Ricordia : Hamilton Soundtrack Review|website=[[Ricordia]]}}</ref> [[Hitfix]] notes that the song's opening stanzas \"have this sort of great simple stripped down quality, just demonstrating how dense the rhyme schemes are, and conveying a lot of information, including a reminder that Hamilton is a face we see every day and rarely consider.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/hamilton-slays-at-the-grammys-as-lin-manuel-miranda-accepts-an-award-in-style#hy52iWi0YVDdXiGh.99|title=Hamilton slays at the Grammys as Lin-Manuel Miranda accepts an award in style|work=HitFix}}</ref> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' wrote that the song has \"booming instrumental, which features dramatic pauses and guitar strings\".<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Monesha|last=Woods|url=http://www.vibe.com/2015/10/hamilton-soundtrack-review/|title=Going H.A.M.: A Track-By-Track Review Of The 'Hamilton' Soundtrack|magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=album|artist=ORIGINAL BROADWAY CAST OF HAMILTON|title=Alexander Hamilton|award=Platinum|relyear=2015|certyear=2019|accessdate=Feb 6, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true|nosales=true}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[s:Letter by Alexander Hamilton on the hurricane of August 1772|Letter by Alexander Hamilton on the hurricane of August 1772]], which is briefly referenced in the song\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Hamilton (musical)}}\n\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about politicians]]\n[[Category:Songs about writers]]\n[[Category:Songs from Hamilton (musical)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lin-Manuel Miranda]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name            = Alexander Hamilton\n| artist          = [[Leslie Odom Jr.]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]], [[Daveed Diggs]], [[Okieriete Onaodowan]], [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], [[Phillipa Soo]], [[Christopher Jackson (actor)|Christopher Jackson]], & the Cast of ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]''\n| album           = [[Hamilton (album)|Hamilton]]\n| released        = 2015\n| recorded        = \n| genre           = \n*[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n*[[show tune]]\n| length          = 3:56\n| writer          = [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Alexander Hamilton'''\" is the opening number for the 2015 musical ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'', a musical biography of American [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Founding Father]] [[Alexander Hamilton]], which premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 2015. [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]] wrote both the music and lyrics to the song. This song features \"alternately rapped and sung exposition\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/hamilton-an-american-musical-original-broadway-cast-recording-mw0002869830|title=Hamilton: An American Musical [Original Broadway Cast Recording]|first=Marcy|last=Donelson|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lin Manuel Miranda White House Poetry Jam 2009.webm|thumb|thumbtime=3:37|left|Lin-Manuel Miranda performs an early version of the song at the White House poetry jam in 2009.|alt=Lin-Manuel Miranda performs an early version of ''Alexander Hamilton'' at the White House Poetry Jam]]\nThis song was originally part of a group of songs entitled \"The Hamilton Mixtape\" and created by [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]] as he started interpreting and adapting  [[Ron Chernow]]'s ''Hamilton'' biography for the stage. He performed this number live at a White House poetry jam in 2009. The ''[[National Review]]'' noted \"The [[Obama family|Obamas]] and the other guests react with more than a touch of surprise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/nrd/articles/415685/funky-founder|title=National Review Online|date=6 April 2015|work=National Review Online}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' writes that \"Miranda later heard that [[Barack Obama|the President's]] first reaction was to remark that [[Timothy Geithner]] had to see this.\"<ref name=\"rebeccamead\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/02/09/hamiltons|title=Hip-Hop Hamilton \u2013 The New Yorker|first=Rebecca|last=Mead|date=9 February 2015|work=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref> The musical, and this song's YouTube video in particular, have influenced education; Miranda said \"I think teachers used just that one clip for the past six years as their intro to Hamilton.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Zach|last=Schonfeld|url=http://www.newsweek.com/hamilton-biggest-thing-broadway-being-taught-classrooms-all-over-424212|title='Hamilton' Biggest Thing Broadway Being Taught Classrooms All Over|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|date=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the song was performed live at the [[Grammy]]s, the first time a song was broadcast live from a Broadway stage for the Hollywood award show. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said they \"wowed\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6875296/hamilton-2016-grammys-performance|title=Hamilton Cast's 2016 Grammys Performance: Alexander Hamilton \u2013 Video \u2013 Billboard|work=Billboard}}</ref> while [[TV Line]] deemed it \"crowd-pleasing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/02/15/hamilton-grammys-2016-video-alexander-performance/|title=[VIDEO] 'Hamilton' Cast Performs 'Alexander Hamilton' at Grammys 2016 \u2013 TVLine|first=Kimberly|last=Roots|work=[[TVLine]]}}</ref> ''Billboard'' deemed it the night's fourth best live musical moment, writing \"the emotional, enervating retelling of American history was one of the night's standout moments\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6875385/2016-grammys-performances-ranked|title=2016 Grammys Performances Ranked From Worst to Best|work=Billboard}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' also deemed it a highlight and wrote \"It's not Hamilton's most compelling set piece, but it's a very solid introduction to the show's characters, cast and themes. For millions that won't be able to make it to Broadway this year, watching it performed on network TV was the next best thing to actually scoring a ticket.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/grammys-2016-20-best-and-worst-moments-224720/amp/|title=Grammys 2016: 20 Best and Worst Moments|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nThis song is explanatory, setting up who the main character is and summarizing the first two decades of his life in a \"bracingly economical synopsis of Hamilton's early years\".<ref name=\"pitchfork.com\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21122-hamilton-original-broadway-cast-recording/|title=Various Artists|work=Pitchfork}}</ref> It also introduces the other major characters of [[Aaron Burr]], [[John Laurens]], [[Thomas Jefferson]], [[James Madison]], [[Elizabeth Schuyler Hamilton|Eliza Schuyler Hamilton]], [[George Washington]], [[Hercules Mulligan]], [[Marquis de Lafayette]], [[Angelica Schuyler Church]], and [[Maria Reynolds]], and briefly describes Hamilton's relationships to many of them. This \"prologue\" to the story, according to [[Patheos]], \"doesn't just bring Hamilton to life, but all of his contemporaries as well\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/moniqueocampowrites/2015/10/14/hamilton-the-musical-an-album-review/|title=Hamilton The Musical: An Album Review|work=Monique Ocampo Writes}}</ref>\n\nThe derogatory terms used in the number to describe Hamilton, including \"bastard\", \"orphan\", \"son of a whore and a Scotsman\" are repeated throughout the musical in  a motif that demonstrates how his upbringing would haunt him for the rest of his life, despite his attempt to escape his childhood misfortunes and climb to the top of the social ladder. This term was \"derived from a contemptuous description by [[John Adams]]\".<ref name=\"rebeccamead\"/>\n\nFor over two centuries both Hamilton and Burr have been well-known for [[Burr\u2013Hamilton duel|their infamous duel]], in which Burr fatally shot Hamilton. In the opening number, Burr himself acknowledges this, essentially giving away the ending. Thus, like the musical ''[[Titanic (musical)|Titanic]]'', the story becomes more about the journey than the destination.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\">{{cite web|first=Elizabeth|last=Logan|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/elizabeth-logan/i-have-an-opinion-on-ever_b_8223496.html|title=I Have an Opinion on Every Song in \"Hamilton\"|date=1 October 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==Analysis==\n''[[The Atlantic]]'' notes that the musical's opening question \"How does a bastard, orphan, son of a whore and a Scotsman, dropped in the middle of a forgotten spot in the Caribbean by providence, impoverished, in squalor grow up to be a hero and a scholar?\" is answered throughout the following two acts, and essentially becomes \"relentless labor\", epitomised in Burr's rise to power, Hamilton's written documents, and Eliza's securing of Hamilton's legacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/hamilton-cast-album-best-album-of-2015/420975/|title=Why the 'Hamilton' Cast Recording Is the Best Album of 2015 \u2013 The Atlantic|first=Spencer|last=Kornhaber|work=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\nUloop argues that Burr is actually ''Hamilton's'' main character, writing that in this opening number \"Lin portrays his Burr as one completely knowing of his crime to come, in the style of ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]''{{'}}s [[Judas]], and with the ferocity of ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis]]''{{'}} [[Javert]].\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Trevor|last=Dunham|url=http://fsu.uloop.com/news/view.php/172609/hamilton-album-review-starting-a-revolution-pt-2|title=Hamilton Album Review: Starting a Revolution Pt. 2|work=Uloop|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:US10dollarbill-Series 2004A.jpg|thumb|The US Treasury canceled plans to replace \"the ten-dollar Founding Father\" on the [[United States ten-dollar bill|ten-dollar bill]] in part because fans of the ''Hamilton'' musical opposed the change.<ref>{{cite news | last = Viagas | first = Robert | title = It's Official: Alexander Hamilton Will Stay on $10 Bill | magazine = [[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]] | date = April 20, 2016 | url = http://www.playbill.com/article/treasury-secretary-to-announce-today-that-hamilton-will-stay-on-10-bill-com-351602 | quote = U.S. Treasury Secretary Jacob J. Lew announced April 20 that founding Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton's portrait will remain on the front of the $10 bill . . . . Fans of the Broadway musical ''Hamilton'' had clamored to keep the man described in the show as the 'ten-dollar Founding Father' on the note.}}</ref>]]\nThe song has received critical acclaim.  ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' argues that the song's wordplay and self-awareness elevates it above other opening numbers that rely on this \"sung exposition\" technique.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/> [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] explains that the song sets the musical tone by incorporating rap while being \"still essentially in musical-theater territory\".<ref name=\"pitchfork.com\"/> With Burr acting as the narrator of this number, ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' comments: \"fitting, somehow, that the man who jealously slew Hamilton in a duel is the first to take up the mystery of his story\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-cm-hamilton-hip-hop-notebook-20151031-column.html|title=Review: 'Hamilton' is a watershed musical that sets a Founding Father's tale to hip-hop|first=Charles |last=McNulty|date=4 November 2015|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]'', rapper [[Talib Kweli]] effusively praised the song as an exemplar of hip-hop, saying, \"My heart swelled with pride after I heard this song, because I was like, 'This right here is hip-hop.' Hip-hop has no boundaries and no limits, and Lin-Manuel and his crew are proving it\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Loretta|last=Charlton|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/10/talib-kweli-analyzes-hamilton.html|title=Talib Kweli Analyzes Hamilton|work=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Ricordia]] described it as \"the anthem of a man that changed the world\", and argued it should be the anthem of all listeners too.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmaricordia.com/2147/entertainment/hamilton-soundtrack-review/#sthash.jCE0eTnI.dpuf|title=Ricordia : Hamilton Soundtrack Review|website=[[Ricordia]]}}</ref> [[Hitfix]] notes that the song's opening stanzas \"have this sort of great simple stripped down quality, just demonstrating how dense the rhyme schemes are, and conveying a lot of information, including a reminder that Hamilton is a face we see every day and rarely consider.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/hamilton-slays-at-the-grammys-as-lin-manuel-miranda-accepts-an-award-in-style#hy52iWi0YVDdXiGh.99|title=Hamilton slays at the Grammys as Lin-Manuel Miranda accepts an award in style|work=HitFix}}</ref> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' wrote that the song has \"booming instrumental, which features dramatic pauses and guitar strings\".<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Monesha|last=Woods|url=http://www.vibe.com/2015/10/hamilton-soundtrack-review/|title=Going H.A.M.: A Track-By-Track Review Of The 'Hamilton' Soundtrack|magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=album|artist=ORIGINAL BROADWAY CAST OF HAMILTON|title=Alexander Hamilton|award=Platinum|relyear=2015|certyear=2019|accessdate=Feb 6, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true|nosales=true}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[s:Letter by Alexander Hamilton on the hurricane of August 1772|Copy of Hamilton's letter describing when \"a hurricane came, and devastation reigned\" in August of 1772; this letter's evocative language prompted his neighbors to take up a collection \"just to send him to the mainland\" where he could get a formal education.]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Hamilton (musical)}}\n\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about politicians]]\n[[Category:Songs about writers]]\n[[Category:Songs from Hamilton (musical)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lin-Manuel Miranda]]\n", "name_user": "TheHardestAspectOfCreatingAnAccountIsAlwaysTheUsername", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Changed the See Also link from an overly-long wikilink into a more brief description. (I'm not entirely certain if \"See Also\" is even the correct section for interwiki links, but I'll leave this hear for now.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Hamilton_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Darla K. Anderson", "text_new": "{{short description|American film producer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Darla K. Anderson\n| image = Darla K. Anderson.jpg\n| birth_name = Darla Kay Anderson\n| caption = Anderson in October 2010 attending 18th Annual [[Hamptons International Film Festival]] Chairman's Reception at the home of Stuart Suna in [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton, New York]]\n| birth_place = [[Glendale, California]], U.S.\n| birth_date = October 22, 1968 (age 51)\n| residence = [[Noe Valley, San Francisco]], [[California]], U.S.<ref name=SFGate />\n| occupation = Film producer\n| employer = [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]] (1993\u20132018)<br />[[Netflix]] (2019\u2013present) \n| yearsactive =\n| spouse = [[Kori Rae]] (2004, 2008\u2013present)<ref name=SFGate />\n}}\n\n'''Darla Kay Anderson''' is an American film producer who formerly worked at [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]].<ref name='guinness'/> She sits on the national board of directors for the [[Producers Guild of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.producersguild.org/?page=officers |title=Officers, Board Members & Staff \u2013 Producers Guild of America |publisher=Producersguild.org |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nShe produced the 2010 film ''[[Toy Story 3]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/10/movies/awardsseason/10bagger.html|title=THE CARPETBAGGER; Animation Advocacy, Pixar Style|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|date=February 10, 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.forbes.com/jennagoudreau/2011/02/25/most-powerful-women-academy-awards-oscars-2011/22nd-annual-producers-guild-awards-show/#content|title=Most Powerful Women of the 2011 Academy Awards|date=February 25, 2011|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711020311/http://blogs.forbes.com/jennagoudreau/2011/02/25/most-powerful-women-academy-awards-oscars-2011/22nd-annual-producers-guild-awards-show/#content|archivedate=July 11, 2011}}</ref> which was nominated for the 2011 [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] and which won the 2011 [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]].\n\nPreviously, Anderson won a Golden Satellite Award for ''[[A Bug's Life]]'', a [[BAFTA]] award for ''A Bug's Life'' and ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'' and a Producer's Guild Award for ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]''.<ref name='pixartalk'/>\n\nThe 2008 [[Guinness Book of World Records]] lists Anderson as having the highest average movie gross for a producer: $221 million per movie,<ref name='guinness'>{{cite book\n|title=2008 [[Guinness Book of World Records]]\n|page=311\n|year=2007\n|publisher=[[Bantam Dell]]\n}}</ref> and in 2011 the Wall Street Journal listed a combined gross for the four movies she's produced of over $2 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/11/05/pixar-producer-darla-k-anderson-on-toy-story-3/|title=Pixar Producer Darla K. Anderson on 'Toy Story 3'|last=Kung|first=Michelle|date=November 5, 2011|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAnderson was born and raised in [[Glendale, California]]. She studied environmental design at [[San Diego State University]]. Before coming to Pixar in 1993,<ref name=\"Grady\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2010-06-13/entertainment/21907925_1_darla-k-anderson-animation-life-savers|title=It was love at first screening for Pixar producer|last=Grady|first=Pam|date=June 13, 2010|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref> she worked as an executive producer at [[Angel Studios]].<ref name='pixartalk'>[http://www.pixartalk.com/pixarians/darla-k-anderson/ Darla K. Anderson], Pixartalk.com, Retrieved February 26, 2010</ref><ref name='variety'>{{cite magazine\n|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018194719/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117969264.html?categoryid=2160&cs=1\n|accessdate=November 21, 2017\n|title=Darla Anderson \u2013 Women's Impact Report 2007 \u2013 Variety\n|author=Ben Fritz\n|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]\n|date=July 30, 2007\n}}</ref> The character Darla in ''[[Finding Nemo]]'' was created by the director and screenwriter [[Andrew Stanton]] to get back at her for playing practical jokes on him.<ref name='pixartalk'/><ref name='variety'/>\n\nOn March 8, 2018, it was announced that after nearly 25 years, Anderson left Pixar to pursue other opportunities.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/coco-oscar-winning-producer-darla-k-anderson-leaving-pixar-1093131|title='Coco' Oscar-Winning Producer Darla K. Anderson Leaving Pixar (Exclusive)|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 8, 2018|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, it was reported that Anderson had signed a multi-year development deal with [[Netflix]], in which she will develop and produce new animated and live-action projects.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lang|first=Brent|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/netflix-pixar-coco-darla-anderson-1203124939/|title=Netflix Signs Development Deal With Oscar-Winning \u2018Coco\u2019 Producer Darla K. Anderson (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Variety|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAnderson is married to [[Kori Rae]], also a Pixar producer, who produced ''[[Monsters University]]''. They live together in [[Noe Valley, San Francisco]].<ref name=SFGate/>\n\nThey met in 1991 when Anderson, a San Francisco newcomer, joined a softball team that Rae managed. Anderson and Rae started dating in 2001, during the last year of ''Monsters, Inc.'' Since then, they have decided not to work together on the same films. They first married on [[Washington's Birthday|Presidents' Day]] 2004 while San Francisco [[San Francisco 2004 same-sex weddings|was issuing same-sex marriage licenses]], but those licenses were voided by the [[Supreme Court of California|state Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/gay-marriage-2004.html|title=California Court Nullifies Same-Sex Marriages|publisher=[[PBS News Hour]]|date=August 12, 2004|accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThey married again in 2008, after that court [[In re Marriage Cases|declared same-sex marriage legal]] but before [[California Proposition 8|Proposition 8]] took effect.<ref name=SFGate>{{cite news|last=Hartlaub|first=Peter|title='The classic lesbian love story': Pixar 'Monsters' producers in love|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2013/06/28/the-classic-lesbian-love-story-pixar-monsters-producers-in-love|accessdate=June 29, 2013|newspaper=SFGate|date=June 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name='statementofvote'>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008_general/sov_complete.pdf|title=Statement of Vote: 2008 General Election|format=PDF|publisher=[[California Secretary of State]]|date=December 13, 2008|accessdate=February 21, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018225250/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008_general/sov_complete.pdf|archivedate=October 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAnderson's nephew, [[Jack Taylor (basketball)|Jack Taylor]], scored an [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]  record 138 points playing [[college basketball]]. She helped him pay to attend basketball camps at upper-tier colleges while he was growing up.<ref>{{cite news|last=Prisbell|first=Eric|title=Once lost in pursuit of points, Grinnell's Jack Taylor finds contentment|date=December 24, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2013/12/23/grinnell-college-iowa-100-point-scorer-jack-taylor/4173599|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6MKtyv1gz?url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2013/12/23/grinnell-college-iowa-100-point-scorer-jack-taylor/4173599|archivedate=January 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Toy Story]]'' || Digital Angel\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Geri's Game]]'' || Special Thanks\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1998 || ''[[It's Tough to Be a Bug]]'' || Executive Producer\n|-\n| ''[[A Bug's Life]]'' ||rowspan=\"2\"| Producer<ref name='amg'>{{cite web\n|title=Darla K. Anderson > Filmography\n|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/darla-k-anderson-265685/filmography\n|accessdate=March 7, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Nichols|first=Peter M.|title=The New York Times guide to the best 1,000 movies ever made|url=https://books.google.com/books?I'd=55glWjbs14sC&pg=PA658|accessdate=March 1, 2011|date=February 3, 2004|publisher=St. Martin's Griffin|isbn=978-0-312-32611-1|pages=658-}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]''\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Mike's New Car]]''||rowspan=\"2\"| Special Thanks\n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Exploring the Reef]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2006 || ''[[Mater and the Ghostlight]]'' || Executive Producer\n|-\n| ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'' || Producer<ref name='amg'/>\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'' ||rowspan=\"2\"| Special Thanks\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]''\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Toy Story 3]]'' || Producer\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2011 || ''[[Hawaiian Vacation]]'' ||rowspan=\"8\"| Special Thanks\n|-\n| ''[[Cars 2]]''\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Brave (2012 film)|Brave]]''\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Monsters University]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2015 || ''[[Sanjay's Super Team]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]''\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Finding Dory]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2017 || ''[[Cars 3]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]''|| Producer<ref name=Variety>{{cite news|last=Dickey|first=Josh|title=Pixar announces Latin-themed feature|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118053093|accessdate=April 25, 2012|newspaper=Variety|date=April 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Graser|first=Marc|title='Finding Nemo' Sequel 'Finding Dory' Swims Thanksgiving 2015|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/pixar-finds-title-release-date-for-finding-nemo-sequel-1200331933/|accessdate=April 18, 2013|newspaper=Variety|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Incredibles 2]]'' || Special Thanks\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of LGBT Academy Award winners and nominees]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|26565|Darla K. Anderson}}\n\n{{Academy Award Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Toy Story}}\n{{Monsters, Inc.}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Darla K.}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:American animated film producers]]\n[[Category:American women film producers]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n[[Category:Pixar people]]\n[[Category:People from Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:San Diego State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Producers who won the Best Animated Feature Academy Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film producer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Darla K. Anderson\n| image = Darla K. Anderson.jpg\n| birth_name = Darla Kay Anderson\n| caption = Anderson in October 2010 attending 18th Annual [[Hamptons International Film Festival]] Chairman's Reception at the home of Stuart Suna in [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton, New York]]\n| birth_place = [[Glendale, California]], U.S.\n| birth_date = October 22, 1968 (age 51)\n| residence = [[Noe Valley, San Francisco]], [[California]], U.S.<ref name=SFGate />\n| occupation = Film producer\n| employer = [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]] (1993\u20132018)<br />[[Netflix]] (2019\u2013present) \n| yearsactive =\n| spouse = [[Kori Rae]] (2004, 2008\u2013present)<ref name=SFGate />\n}}\n\n'''Darla Kay Anderson''' is an American film producer who formerly worked at [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]].<ref name='guinness'/> She sits on the national board of directors for the [[Producers Guild of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.producersguild.org/?page=officers |title=Officers, Board Members & Staff \u2013 Producers Guild of America |publisher=Producersguild.org |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nShe produced the 2010 film ''[[Toy Story 3]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/10/movies/awardsseason/10bagger.html|title=THE CARPETBAGGER; Animation Advocacy, Pixar Style|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|date=February 10, 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.forbes.com/jennagoudreau/2011/02/25/most-powerful-women-academy-awards-oscars-2011/22nd-annual-producers-guild-awards-show/#content|title=Most Powerful Women of the 2011 Academy Awards|date=February 25, 2011|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711020311/http://blogs.forbes.com/jennagoudreau/2011/02/25/most-powerful-women-academy-awards-oscars-2011/22nd-annual-producers-guild-awards-show/#content|archivedate=July 11, 2011}}</ref> which was nominated for the 2011 [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] and which won the 2011 [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]].\n\nPreviously, Anderson won a Golden Satellite Award for ''[[A Bug's Life]]'', a [[BAFTA]] award for ''A Bug's Life'' and ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'' and a Producer's Guild Award for ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]''.<ref name='pixartalk'/>\n\nThe 2008 [[Guinness Book of World Records]] lists Anderson as having the highest average movie gross for a producer: $221 million per movie,<ref name='guinness'>{{cite book\n|title=2008 [[Guinness Book of World Records]]\n|page=311\n|year=2007\n|publisher=[[Bantam Dell]]\n}}</ref> and in 2011 the Wall Street Journal listed a combined gross for the four movies she's produced of over $2 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/11/05/pixar-producer-darla-k-anderson-on-toy-story-3/|title=Pixar Producer Darla K. Anderson on 'Toy Story 3'|last=Kung|first=Michelle|date=November 5, 2011|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAnderson was born and raised in [[Glendale, California]]. She studied environmental design at [[San Diego State University]]. Before coming to Pixar in 1993,<ref name=\"Grady\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2010-06-13/entertainment/21907925_1_darla-k-anderson-animation-life-savers|title=It was love at first screening for Pixar producer|last=Grady|first=Pam|date=June 13, 2010|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref> she worked as an executive producer at [[Angel Studios]].<ref name='pixartalk'>[http://www.pixartalk.com/pixarians/darla-k-anderson/ Darla K. Anderson], Pixartalk.com, Retrieved February 26, 2010</ref><ref name='variety'>{{cite magazine\n|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018194719/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117969264.html?categoryid=2160&cs=1\n|accessdate=November 21, 2017\n|title=Darla Anderson \u2013 Women's Impact Report 2007 \u2013 Variety\n|author=Ben Fritz\n|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]\n|date=July 30, 2007\n}}</ref> The character Darla in ''[[Finding Nemo]]'' was created by the director and screenwriter [[Andrew Stanton]] to get back at her for playing practical jokes on him.<ref name='pixartalk'/><ref name='variety'/>\n\nOn March 8, 2018, it was announced that after nearly 25 years, Anderson left Pixar to pursue other opportunities.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/coco-oscar-winning-producer-darla-k-anderson-leaving-pixar-1093131|title='Coco' Oscar-Winning Producer Darla K. Anderson Leaving Pixar (Exclusive)|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 8, 2018|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, it was reported that Anderson had signed a multi-year development deal with [[Netflix]], in which she will develop and produce new animated and live-action projects.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lang|first=Brent|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/netflix-pixar-coco-darla-anderson-1203124939/|title=Netflix Signs Development Deal With Oscar-Winning \u2018Coco\u2019 Producer Darla K. Anderson (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Variety|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAnderson is married to [[Kori Rae]], also a Pixar producer, who produced ''[[Monsters University]]''. They live together in [[Noe Valley, San Francisco]].<ref name=SFGate/>\n\nThey met in 1991 when Anderson, a San Francisco newcomer, joined a softball team that Rae managed. Anderson and Rae started dating in 2001, during the last year of ''Monsters, Inc.'' Since then, they have decided not to work together on the same films. They first married on [[Washington's Birthday|Presidents' Day]] 2004 while San Francisco [[San Francisco 2004 same-sex weddings|was issuing same-sex marriage licenses]], but those licenses were voided by the [[Supreme Court of California|state Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/gay-marriage-2004.html|title=California Court Nullifies Same-Sex Marriages|publisher=[[PBS News Hour]]|date=August 12, 2004|accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThey married again in 2008, after that court [[In re Marriage Cases|declared same-sex marriage legal]] but before [[California Proposition 8|Proposition 8]] took effect.<ref name=SFGate>{{cite news|last=Hartlaub|first=Peter|title='The classic lesbian love story': Pixar 'Monsters' producers in love|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2013/06/28/the-classic-lesbian-love-story-pixar-monsters-producers-in-love|accessdate=June 29, 2013|newspaper=SFGate|date=June 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name='statementofvote'>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008_general/sov_complete.pdf|title=Statement of Vote: 2008 General Election|format=PDF|publisher=[[California Secretary of State]]|date=December 13, 2008|accessdate=February 21, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018225250/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008_general/sov_complete.pdf|archivedate=October 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAnderson's nephew, [[Jack Taylor (basketball)|Jack Taylor]], scored an [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]  record 138 points playing [[college basketball]]. She helped him pay to attend basketball camps at upper-tier colleges while he was growing up.<ref>{{cite news|last=Prisbell|first=Eric|title=Once lost in pursuit of points, Grinnell's Jack Taylor finds contentment|date=December 24, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2013/12/23/grinnell-college-iowa-100-point-scorer-jack-taylor/4173599|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6MKtyv1gz?url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2013/12/23/grinnell-college-iowa-100-point-scorer-jack-taylor/4173599|archivedate=January 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Toy Story]]'' || Digital Angel\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Geri's Game]]'' || Special Thanks\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1998 || ''[[It's Tough to Be a Bug]]'' || Executive Producer\n|-\n| ''[[A Bug's Life]]'' ||rowspan=\"2\"| Producer<ref name='amg'>{{cite web\n|title=Darla K. Anderson > Filmography\n|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/darla-k-anderson-265685/filmography\n|accessdate=March 7, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Nichols|first=Peter M.|title=The New York Times guide to the best 1,000 movies ever made|url=https://books.google.com/books?I'd=55glWjbs14sC&pg=PA658|accessdate=March 1, 2011|date=February 3, 2004|publisher=St. Martin's Griffin|isbn=978-0-312-32611-1|pages=658-}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]''\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Mike's New Car]]''||rowspan=\"2\"| Special Thanks\n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Exploring the Reef]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2006 || ''[[Mater and the Ghostlight]]'' || Executive Producer\n|-\n| ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'' || Producer<ref name='amg'/>\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'' ||rowspan=\"2\"| Special Thanks\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]''\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Toy Story 3]]'' || Producer\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2011 || ''[[Hawaiian Vacation]]'' ||rowspan=\"8\"| Special Thanks\n|-\n| ''[[Cars 2]]''\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Brave (2012 film)|Brave]]''\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Monsters University]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2015 || ''[[Sanjay's Super Team]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]''\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Finding Dory]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2017 || ''[[Cars 3]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]''|| Producer<ref name=Variety>{{cite news|last=Dickey|first=Josh|title=Pixar announces Latin-themed feature|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118053093|accessdate=April 25, 2012|newspaper=Variety|date=April 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Graser|first=Marc|title='Finding Nemo' Sequel 'Finding Dory' Swims Thanksgiving 2015|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/pixar-finds-title-release-date-for-finding-nemo-sequel-1200331933/|accessdate=April 18, 2013|newspaper=Variety|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of LGBT Academy Award winners and nominees]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|26565|Darla K. Anderson}}\n\n{{Academy Award Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Toy Story}}\n{{Monsters, Inc.}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Darla K.}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:American animated film producers]]\n[[Category:American women film producers]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n[[Category:Pixar people]]\n[[Category:People from Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:San Diego State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Producers who won the Best Animated Feature Academy Award]]\n", "name_user": "2601:cb:8200:7220:6444:8629:a7dc:c401", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darla_K._Anderson"}
{"title_page": "David Bowles (author)", "text_new": "{{short description|American poet, translator and author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| birth_name = David Oscar Bowles, Jr.\n| image = David Bowles 2018.jpg\n| caption = Bowles at the 2018 Texas Book Festival\n| alt = An image of author David Bowles taken in June of 2016.\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1970|2|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]], [[United States]]\n| occupation = Poet, novelist, translator\n| notableworks = ''The Smoking Mirror'' <br> ''They Call Me G\u00fcero''\n| awards = [[Belpr\u00e9 Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Author Honor]]; [[Texas Institute of Letters|Texas Institute of Letters Translation Award]]; [[We Need Diverse Books|Walter Dean Myers Honor]]; [[Bank Street College of Education|Claudia Lewis Award for Excellence in Poetry]]; [[Tom\u00e1s Rivera Award|Tom\u00e1s Rivera Mexican American Children\u2019s Book Award]]\n| website = {{url|www.davidbowles.us}}\n}}\n\n'''David Bowles''' (born 1970) is an American poet, translator and author.\n\n==Life and career==\n\nDavid Bowles was born to residents of the [[Rio Grande Valley]] of Texas in 1970. He is of Mexican descent.{{sfn|Bowles on Inclusive Literature}}\n \nMuch of Bowles' work stems from his research into border legends and pre-Columbian Mesoamerican mythology, featured on [[Monsters and Mysteries in America]].{{sfn|Donna Author on National TV}} He is currently developing a TV series based on his book ''Border Lore'' with Mucho M\u00e1s Media and Campanario Entertainment.{{sfn|This Is Horror}}\n\nIn addition, Bowles has translated multiple books, poems and stories from languages as diverse as [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Nahuatl]],{{sfn|Flower, Song, Dance}} [[Yucatec Mayan]],{{sfn|Perform with Drums}} and [[Japanese language|Japanese]].{{sfn|Meet David Bowles}} He is also a poet, with two books of verse and poems published widely.{{sfn|Interview with David Bowles}}\n\nBowles also writes speculative fiction,{{sfn|Interview with David Bowles}} such as his MG/YA fantasy series ''Garza Twins'',{{sfn|TSM Postcard}} that features Latino protagonists and Mesoamerican mythology.{{sfn|Bowles on Inclusive Literature}} He worked with [[Adam Gidwitz]] on the ''Unicorn Rescue Society'' series for [[Dutton Penguin]].{{sfn|In the Beginning}} His speculative fiction work includes graphic novels like the steampunk title ''Clockwork Curandera'' he created with illustrator [[Ra\u00fal the Third|Ra\u00fal \"the Third\" Gonz\u00e1lez]].{{sfn|Book Deals}}\n\nBowles resides in [[Donna, Texas]]. Holding a Master's in English and a doctorate in Education, he is a professor in the Department of Literatures & Cultural Studies at the [[University of Texas Rio Grande Valley]], where he teaches children's/adolescent literature and [[Nahuatl]].{{sfn|UTRGV}} {{sfn|Donna Author on National TV}}\n\nIn February 2017, David Bowles was elected to the [[Texas Institute of Letters]].{{sfn|TIL 2017}} In January 2020, he co-founded the hashtag / literary activist campaign [[DignidadLiteraria|#DignidadLiteraria]].\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* ''Flower, Song, Dance: Aztec and Mayan Poetry'': awarded the [[Texas Institute of Letters]]' 2014 Soeurette Diehl Fraser Award for Best Translation.{{sfn|TIL Award List}}\n* TOP SHELF Book Review Column: received a 2014 Texas [[Associated Press]] Managing Editors' Headliners Excellence in Journalism Award for Comment and Criticism.{{sfn|TAPME Award List}}\n* ''The Smoking Mirror'' was selected as a [[Belpr\u00e9 Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Honor Book]] in 2016 by the [[American Library Association]].{{sfn|2016 ALA Winners}}\n* Inducted into the [[Texas Institute of Letters]] in 2017.{{sfn|TIL 2017}}\n*''They Call Me G\u00fcero'' has received multiple accolades: \n**Selected Best Book of 2018 by the [[School Library Journal]]\n**Selected a 2019 Notable Verse Novel by the [[National Council of Teachers of English|NCTE]] Award for Excellence in Children\u2019s Poetry Committee\n**Named one of the 2018 Best Children's & Teen Books of the Year by [[Shelf Awareness]]. \n**2019 Honor Book for the [[We Need Diverse Books|Walter Dean Myers Award for Outstanding Children's Literature]] in the Younger Reader category.\n**2019 [[Belpr\u00e9 Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Honor Book]]\n**2019 [[Bank Street College of Education|Claudia Lewis Award for Excellence in Poetry]]\n**[[Association for Library Service to Children]] Notable Children's Book, 2019\n**2019 [[Tom\u00e1s Rivera Award|Tom\u00e1s Rivera Mexican American Children\u2019s Book Award]] \n**2018 Jean Flynn Award for Best Middle Grade Book from the [[Texas Institute of Letters]]\n**Selected for the 2020-2021 Texas Bluebonnet Award Master List by the [[Texas Library Association]]\n**The [[International Youth Library]] Foundation named it a White Raven, a recommended title for international children\u2019s and youth literature.\n*''Feathered Serpent, Dark Heart of Sky'' received the [[Texas Institute of Letters]] Award for Best Young Adult Book. It was also selected a Best YA Book of 2018 by [[Kirkus Reviews]] and was a [[YALSA Award for Excellence in Nonfiction|YALSA Award Nominee for Excellence in Nonfiction]].\n\n==Works==\nAS AUTHOR\n\n'''Novels'''\n* ''The Chupacabras of the Rio Grande'' (The Unicorn Rescue Society, #4). Co-authored by [[Adam Gidwitz]]. Illustrated by Hatem Aly. New York: [[Dutton Penguin]], 2019.\n* ''Lords of the Earth''. Hobart, Australia: Severed Press, 2016.\n*Garza Twins Series\n** ''The Smoking Mirror'' (#1). Melbourne: [[IFWG Publishing]], 2015.\n** ''A Kingdom Beneath the Waves'' (#2). Melbourne: [[IFWG Publishing]], 2016.\n** ''The Hidden City''. (#3). Melbourne: [[IFWG Publishing]], 2018.\n\n'''Story Collections'''\n* ''Chupacabra Vengeance''. Tigard, Oregon: Broken River Books, 2017.\n* ''The Seed: Stories from the River's Edge''. Spring, TX: Absey & Co., 2011.\n\n'''Graphic Novels'''\n* '''Tales of the Feathered Serpent''' series\n**''Rise of the Halfling King''. Illustrated by Charlene Bowles. El Paso, TX: [[Cinco Puntos Press]], 2020. (Forthcoming.) \n* '''Clockwork Curandera''' series\n** ''Vol. 1\u2014The Witch Owl Parliament''. Illustrated by Ra\u00fal the Third. New York, NY: [[Tu Books]], 2020. (Forthcoming.)\n\n'''Chapter Books'''\n*'''13th Street''' series\n**''Battle of the Bad-Breath Bats'' (#1). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n**''The Fire-Breathing Ferret Fiasco'' (#2). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n**''Clash of the Cackling Cougars'' (#3). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n**''The Shocking Shark Showdown'' (#4). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n\n'''Myth and Legend'''\n* ''Feathered Serpent, Dark Heart of Sky: Myths of Mexico''. El Paso, TX: [[Cinco Puntos Press]], 2018.\n* ''Ghosts of the Rio Grande Valley''. Charleston: [[The History Press]], 2016.\n* ''Border Lore: Folktales and Legends of South Texas''. Beaumont, TX: [[Lamar University|Lamar University Press]], 2015.\n* ''Creature Feature: 13 Frightening Folktales of the Rio Grande Valley''. McAllen, TX: AIM Media Texas, 2013.\n* ''Mexican Bestiary''. Donna, TX: VAO Publishing, 2012.\n\n'''Poetry'''\n* ''They Call Me G\u00fcero: A Border Kid's Poems''. El Paso, TX: [[Cinco Puntos Press]], 2018. \n* ''Shattering and Bricolage''. Dallas, TX: Ink Brush Press, 2014.\n\nAS TRANSLATOR\n* ''The Sea-Ringed World: Sacred Stories of the Americas''. Translation of ''Diccionario de mitos de Am\u00e9rica'' by Mar\u00eda Garc\u00eda Esper\u00f3n. New York, NY: Levine Querido. 2021 (forthcoming).\n* ''Me dicen G\u00fcero: Poemas de un chavo fronterizo''. Translation of ''They Call Me G\u00fcero.'' New York, NY: Vintage Espa\u00f1ol. 2020 (forthcoming).\n* ''Snake Poems: An Aztec Invocation''. Special Edition for Camino Del Sol Series. Nahuatl translation of the original text by [[Francisco X. Alarc\u00f3n]]. Tucson, AZ: [[University of Arizona Press]]. March 12, 2019.\n* ''El verano de las mariposas''. Translation of ''Summer of the Mariposas'' by Guadalupe Garc\u00eda McCall. New York, NY: [[Tu Books]], 2018.\n* ''Flower, Song, Dance: Aztec and Mayan Poetry''. Beaumont, TX: [[Lamar University|Lamar University Press]], 2013.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite web|author=Adam Gidwitz|year=2018|title=In the Beginning Was the Name|url=https://nerdybookclub.wordpress.com/2017/12/14/in-the-beginning-was-the-name-by-adam-gidwitz/|work=Nerdy Book Club|publisher=Nerdy Book Club|accessdate=2018-01-08|ref={{sfnref|In the Beginning}}}}\n* {{cite web |author=Madeline Smither |year=2014 |title=Donna author to talk about 'Big Bird' local legend on national TV |url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/local/article_a66d697c-9455-11e3-b2db-0017a43b2370.html |work=The Monitor |publisher=The Monitor |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Donna Author on National TV}} }}\n* {{cite news |last=Rasmussen |first=Peter |date=July 28, 2015 |title=''The Smoking Mirror'': Stories of Shapeshifting Drive Bowles\u2019 New Novel  |url=http://www.themonitor.com/life/vidaeducation/the-smoking-mirror-stories-of-shapeshifting-drives-bowles-new-novel/article_9fb0c070-353a-11e5-818f-e7e2fb9f8554.html |publisher=The Monitor |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Stories of Shapeshifting}} }}\n* {{cite news |last=Vourvoulias |first=Sabrina |date=April 10, 2015 |title=Meet David Bowles, author of ''The Smoking Mirror'' |url=http://aldianews.com/articles/culture/literature/meet-david-bowles-author-smoking-mirror/38586 |publisher=AL D\u00cdA |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Meet David Bowles}} }}\n* {{cite web |last=Vourvoulias |first=Sabrina |date=June 29, 2015 |title=Introduction to \"Winds that Stir Vermillion Sands\" |url=http://www.strangehorizons.com/2015/20150629/1bowlesintro-f.shtml |publisher=Strange Horizons |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Introduction}} }}\n* {{cite web |last=Fowler |first=Olivia |year=2015 |title=Author Interview: David Bowles on Inclusive Literature, the Hugos, and